{"title_page": "Bibala", "text_new": "'''Bibala'''  (known as Vila Arriaga until 1975) is a town, with a population of 10,500 (2014)<ref>[https://www.citypopulation.de/en/angola/cities/ Citypopulation.de] Population of cities & urban localities in Angola</ref>, and a municipality in southern [[Angola]].  It lies in [[Namibe Province]]. The municipality of Bibala covers {{convert|7700|km2|mi2}} with a population of 64,504 (2014).<ref>[https://www.citypopulation.de/en/angola/admin/ Citypopulation.de] Population of provinces and municipalities in Angola</ref>\n\nIt is bordered to the north by the municipality of [[Camucuio]], to the east by [[Quilengues]], [[Cacula]], [[Lubango]] and [[Humpata]], to the south by [[Virei]], and to the west by [[Namibe]]. It is composed of the communes of [[Bibala-Sede]], [[Caitou]], [[Lola (Namibe)|Lola]] e [[Kapagombe]].\n\n== Transport ==\n\nIt is served by a station on the southern network of [[Angolan Railways]].\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Railway stations in Angola]]\n* [[Transport in Angola]]\n\n== References ==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{coord|14|46|00|S|13|21|00|E|region:AO_type:city|display=title}}\n\n{{Municipalities of Angola}}\n\n[[Category:Populated places in Namibe Province]]\n[[Category:Municipalities of Angola]]\n\n{{Angola-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Bibala'''  (known as Vila Arriaga until 1975) is a town, with a population of 10,500 (2014)<ref>[https://www.citypopulation.de/en/angola/cities/ Citypopulation.de] Population of cities & urban localities in Angola</ref>, and a municipality in southern [[Angola]].  It lies in [[Namibe Province]]. The municipality of Bibala covers {{convert|7700|km2|mi2}} with a population of 64,504 (2014)<ref>[https://www.citypopulation.de/en/angola/admin/ Citypopulation.de] Population of provinces and municipalities in Angola</ref>.\n\nIt is bordered to the north by the municipality of [[Camucuio]], to the east by [[Quilengues]], [[Cacula]], [[Lubango]] and [[Humpata]], to the south by [[Virei]], and to the west by [[Namibe]]. It is composed of the communes of [[Bibala-Sede]], [[Caitou]], [[Lola (Namibe)|Lola]] e [[Kapagombe]].\n\n== Transport ==\n\nIt is served by a station on the southern network of [[Angolan Railways]].\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Railway stations in Angola]]\n* [[Transport in Angola]]\n\n== References ==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{coord|14|46|00|S|13|21|00|E|region:AO_type:city|display=title}}\n\n{{Municipalities of Angola}}\n\n[[Category:Populated places in Namibe Province]]\n[[Category:Municipalities of Angola]]\n\n{{Angola-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "DannyS712", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing the location of periods / full stops", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bibala"}
{"title_page": "Bristol Energy", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n\n{{Infobox company\n| name                = Bristol Energy Limited\n| logo                = File:BristolEnergyLogo.png\n| type                = [[Limited Company]]\n| industry            = Utilities\n| fate                = \n| predecessor         = <!-- or: | predecessors = -->\n| successor           = <!-- or: | successors = -->\n| founded             = {{Start date and age|2015|11|02}} in [[Bristol]], UK\n| founder             = \n| defunct             = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| hq_location_city    = Bristol\n| hq_location_country = UK\n| area_served         = United Kingdom\n| key_people          = Allan Booth (Managing Director)\n| products            = [[Natural gas|Gas]]<br />[[Electricity]]<br />[[Renewable Energy]]\n| revenue             = {{Unbulleted list|{{Increase}} [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]76.2 million (2019)|{{Increase}} [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]52.5 million (2018)|{{Increase}} [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]13.7 million (2017)}}\n| revenue_year        = \n| net_income          = {{Unbulleted list|{{Increase}} [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]](10.1) million (2019)|{{Decrease}} [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]](10.3) million (2018)|{{Decrease}} [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]](8.4) million (2017)}}\n| net_income_year     = \n| owner               = <!-- or: | owners = -->\n| num_employees       = {{Unbulleted list|{{increase}} 200 (2019)|{{increase}} 161 (2018)}}\n| num_employees_year  = \n| parent              = [[Bristol City Council]]\n| website             = {{Official URL}}\n}}\n\n'''Bristol Energy''' is a municipally owned energy supply company, founded in September 2015 by [[Bristol City Council]]. The company supplies gas and electricity to domestic and business customers across the United Kingdom.\n\n== History ==\nThe company began trading in November 2015. In spring 2018 it lost the contract to supply energy to Bristol City Council after [[British Gas]] marginally undercut them on price.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bristolpost.co.uk/news/bristol-news/bristol-city-council-drops-bristol-1499376|title=Council drops Bristol Energy as green energy provider - despite owning it|last=Wilson|first=Kate|date=2018-04-25|website=bristolpost|access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2018, employee number one and CEO Peter Haigh stood down and was replaced by Marek Majewicz, the company's finance director.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bristolpost.co.uk/news/bristol-news/loss-making-bristol-energys-managing-2351145|title=Managing director of loss-making Bristol Energy leaves|last=Wilson|first=Kate|date=2018-12-20|website=Bristol Post|access-date=2019-08-07}}</ref> In November 2018 Bristol Energy began supplying gas to Bristol City Council again, winning back part of the business it had lost to British Gas.\n\nIn January 2019, Bristol Energy announced it had received a \u20ac1.9m grant from the European Investment Bank and the European Commission to fund renewable energy, in partnership with [[Plymouth City Council]].<ref>[https://www.solarpowerportal.co.uk/news/bristol_to_launch_new_wave_of_south_west_clean_energy_projects_with_europea Bristol to launch \u2018new wave\u2019 of South West clean energy projects with European funding] (14 January 2019) Solar Power Portal.</ref> In that year, 79% of the company's energy supply was generated from renewable sources.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bristol-energy.co.uk/our-social-impact-2018-2019|title=Our Social Impact 2018\u20132019|last=|first=|date=|website=Bristol Energy|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-08-06}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2019 it regained the contract to supply electricity to Bristol City Council.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bristolpost.co.uk/news/bristol-news/british-gas-electricity-bristol-energy-2543970|title=Bristol Energy wins council contract after missing out last year|last=Wilson|first=Kate|date=2019-02-14|website=Bristol Post|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref> \n\nIn May 2019 Bristol Energy began a partnership with The Big Issue.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bigissue.com/latest/save-cash-and-go-green-with-the-big-issue-green-tariff-from-bristol-energy/|title=Save cash and go green with The Big Issue Green Tariff from Bristol Energy|date=2019-05-13|website=The Big Issue|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> \n\nIn August 2019 the then CEO revealed the company had employed and continued to employ two people who were previously homeless.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bristolpost.co.uk/news/bristol-news/bristol-energy-accused-spin-performance-3221092|title=Bristol Energy accused of ' spin' over director's exit package|last=Cameron|first=Amanda|date=2019-08-19|website=bristolpost|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> \n\n{{As of|2019|August|df=}}, the company had received some \u00a337.7 million of funding from Bristol City Council and was not expected to be profitable until 2024.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-bristol-49293475|title=Energy firm 'might not make profit for five years'|date=2019-08-09|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-02-29|language=en-GB}}</ref> \n\nIn March 2020 Marek Majewicz departed as Managing and Finance Director.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Gnome|first=Lord|url=|title=Rotten Boroughs - To Be or Not to Be|date=3 April 2020|work=Private Eye|access-date=|url-status=live|publisher=Pressdram Limited}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2020 Allan Booth a turnaround expert was appointed as MD, his most recent appointment, Towcester Racecourse Company Limited is currently in liquidation, it has failed to file accounts at [[Companies House]] since his appointment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://beta.companieshouse.gov.uk/company/00230773|title=TOWCESTER RACECOURSE COMPANY,LIMITED(THE) - Overview (free company information from Companies House)|website=beta.companieshouse.gov.uk|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n== Corporate Social Responsibility ==\nSince its creation in 2015, the Social Value Portal estimate Bristol Energy has delivered over \u00a312 million of social value back into Bristol. The company measures the amount of social value they have delivered using the National Social Value Measurement (TOMs - Themes, Outcomes and Measures) framework.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://socialvalueportal.com/national-toms/|title=National TOMs|date=2017-10-18|website=Social Value Portal|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref>\n\nBristol Energy delivered \u00a37 million of social value back into Bristol in 2018/19.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bristol-energy.co.uk/our-social-impact-2018-2019|title=Our social impact 2018-2019 {{!}} Bristol Energy|website=www.bristol-energy.co.uk|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref> \n\nBristol Energy set up its Fuel Good Fund<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bristolpost.co.uk/special-features/what-its-like-live-fuel-2667631|title=What it's like to live in fuel poverty in Bristol|last=Reeves|first=Millie|date=2019-03-25|website=bristolpost|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref> in a bid to help tackle fuel poverty. Since 2015, the energy company has raised over \u00a350,000 through the Fuel Good Fund.\n\nIn November 2017, Bristol Energy established the 'No Cold Homes' initiative to help tackle fuel poverty in Bristol. Led by Bristol Mayor Marvin Rees, the Centre for Sustainable Energy, Bristol Energy and Western Power Distribution, brought together charities, business leaders and influencers from across the city to share knowledge and develop an action plan for collaborative work.\n\nDonations include:\n\n* \u00a32,000 to charity Feeding Bristol's Healthy Holidays Programme in 2019, to help provide food for thousands of children in Bristol at risk of going without during the holiday period.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.feedingbristol.org/healthy-holidays|title=Healthy Holidays|website=Feeding Bristol|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref>\n* \u00a325,000 to the Centre for Sustainable Energy towards their Warmer Homes Advice and Money (WHAM) project in 2019.\n* A further \u00a350,000 to the Bristol-based Centre for Sustainable Energy to help fund the Fuel Poverty Action Plan, due to launch in 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cse.org.uk/news/view/2321|title=\u00a325k Wham boost ...|website=www.cse.org.uk|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref>\n\n==Customer numbers==\nNumbers are the number of meter points served at the financial year end, 31 March, as published in the annual accounts and filed at Companies House.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://beta.companieshouse.gov.uk/company/09135084/filing-history/MzI0OTMwNDU5MmFkaXF6a2N4/document?format=pdf&download=0|title=Annual accounts 2018-19 as filed at companies house|last=|first=|date=15 Nov 2019|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=29 Feb 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{Unbulleted list|{{Increase}} 165,000 (2019)|{{Increase}} 120,000 (2018)|{{Increase}} 58,000 (2017)}}\n\n== Financial structure ==\nBristol Energy is wholly owned by Bristol City Council through an intermediate [[holding company]], Bristol Holding Limited (which also has Bristol Waste Company Limited as a subsidiary).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://beta.companieshouse.gov.uk/company/09485669/filing-history/MzI0OTMwNDU5MWFkaXF6a2N4/document?format=pdf&download=0|title=Bristol Holding Ltd: Annual Report|last=|first=|date=March 2019|website=|page=19|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=29 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Robin Hood Energy]] \u2013 a similar company owned by Nottingham City Council\n*[[London Power]] \u2013 a similar company owned by the Greater London Authority\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website}}\n\n[[Category:2015 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Non-profit organisations based in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Electric power companies of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Bristol]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n\n{{Infobox company\n| name                = Bristol Energy Limited\n| logo                = File:BristolEnergyLogo.png\n| type                = [[Limited Company]]\n| industry            = Utilities\n| fate                = \n| predecessor         = <!-- or: | predecessors = -->\n| successor           = <!-- or: | successors = -->\n| founded             = {{Start date and age|2015|11|02}} in [[Bristol]], UK\n| founder             = \n| defunct             = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| hq_location_city    = Bristol\n| hq_location_country = UK\n| area_served         = United Kingdom\n| key_people          = Allan Booth (Managing Director)\n| products            = [[Natural gas|Gas]]<br />[[Electricity]]<br />[[Renewable Energy]]\n| revenue             = {{Unbulleted list|{{Increase}} [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]76.2 million (2019)|{{Increase}} [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]52.5 million (2018)|{{Increase}} [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]13.7 million (2017)}}\n| revenue_year        = \n| net_income          = {{Unbulleted list|{{Increase}} [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]](10.1) million (2019)|{{Decrease}} [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]](10.3) million (2018)|{{Decrease}} [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]](8.4) million (2017)}}\n| net_income_year     = \n| owner               = <!-- or: | owners = -->\n| num_employees       = {{Unbulleted list|{{increase}} 200 (2019)|{{increase}} 161 (2018)}}\n| num_employees_year  = \n| parent              = [[Bristol City Council]]\n| website             = {{Official URL}}\n}}\n\n'''Bristol Energy''' is a municipally owned energy supply company, founded in September 2015 by [[Bristol City Council]]. The company supplies gas and electricity to domestic and business customers across the United Kingdom.\n\n== History ==\nThe company began trading in November 2015. In spring 2018 it lost the contract to supply energy to Bristol City Council after [[British Gas]] marginally 