{"title_page": "Jim Flaherty", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2014}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix = [[The Honourable]]\n|birthname        = James Michael Flaherty\n|honorific-suffix = [[Queen's Privy Council for Canada|PC]], [[Meritorious Service Cross|MSC]]<ref name=\"canadagazette.gc.ca\">http://canadagazette.gc.ca/rp-pr/p1/2017/2017-07-01/html/gh-rg-eng.html</ref>  \n|image            = Jim Flaherty 2007.JPG\n\n|office           = [[Minister of Finance (Canada)|Minister of Finance]]\n|primeminister    = [[Stephen Harper]]\n|term_start       = February 6, 2006\n|term_end         = March 18, 2014\n|predecessor      = [[Ralph Goodale]]\n|successor        = [[Joe Oliver (politician)|Joe Oliver]]\n\n|constituency_MP1 = [[Whitby\u2014Oshawa|Whitby-Oshawa]]\n|parliament1      = Canadian\n|term_start1      = January 23, 2006\n|term_end1        = April 10, 2014\n|predecessor1     = [[Judi Longfield]]\n|successor1       = [[Pat Perkins]]\n\n|office2          = 6th [[Deputy Premier of Ontario]]\n|term_start2      = February 8, 2001\n|term_end2        = April 14, 2002\n|premier2         = [[Mike Harris]]\n|predecessor2     = [[Ernie Eves]]\n|successor2       = [[Elizabeth Witmer]]\n\n|office3          = [[Member of Provincial Parliament (Ontario)|Ontario MPP]]\n|term_start3      = 1999\n|term_end3        = 2005\n|predecessor3     = ''New riding''\n|successor3       = [[Christine Elliott]]\n|constituency3    = [[Whitby\u2014Ajax|Whitby-Ajax]]\n\n|term_start4      = 1995\n|term_end4        = 1999\n|predecessor4     = [[Drummond White]]\n|successor4       = ''Riding abolished''\n|constituency4    = [[Durham Centre (provincial electoral district)|Durham Centre]]\n\n|birth_date       = {{birth date|1949|12|30|mf=y}}\n|birth_place      = [[Lachine, Quebec]], Canada\n|death_date       = {{death date and age|2014|04|10|1949|12|30|mf=yes}}\n|death_place      = [[Ottawa|Ottawa, Ontario]], Canada\n|party            = [[Conservative Party of Canada|Conservative Party]]\n|spouse           = [[Christine Elliott]] {{small|(1986\u20132014)}}\n|children         = 3\n|alma_mater       = [[Princeton University]]<br />[[Osgoode Hall Law School|York University]]\n}}\n'''James Michael Flaherty''', {{Post-nominals|country=CAN|PC|MSC}} (December 30, 1949 \u2013 April 10, 2014) was a Canadian politician who served as [[Canada]]'s [[Minister of Finance (Canada)|federal Minister of Finance]] (2006\u20132014) and a [[Ministry of Finance (Ontario)|provincial Minister of Finance]] for [[Ontario]] (2001\u20132002). From 1995 until 2005, he was the [[Member of Provincial Parliament (Ontario)|Member of Provincial Parliament]] for [[Whitby\u2014Ajax]], and a member of the [[Progressive Conservative Party of Ontario|Ontario Progressive Conservative Party]] caucus and unsuccessfully sought the leadership of the provincial party on two occasions.\n\nFlaherty won the riding of [[Whitby\u2014Oshawa]] in the [[2006 Canadian federal election|federal election]] held January 23, 2006, as a member of the [[Conservative Party of Canada]] narrowly beating [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]] incumbent [[Judi Longfield]]. He was re-elected in [[2008 Canadian federal election|2008]] and [[2011 Canadian federal election|2011]]. Flaherty's widow, [[Christine Elliott]], is currently the [[Deputy Premier of Ontario]].\n\n==Education and early career==\nFlaherty was born on December 30, 1949<ref name=\"Jim Flaherty, 64, dies at Ottawa home one month after resigning as finance minister\">{{cite news|title=Jim Flaherty, 64, dies at Ottawa home one month after resigning as finance minister|url=http://news.nationalpost.com/2014/04/10/jim-flaherty-has-died-sources-say-paramedics-outside-former-finance-minsters-condo/|accessdate=April 10, 2014|newspaper=National Post|date=April 10, 2014|author=National Post staff|author2=Postmedia News}}</ref> in [[Lachine, Quebec]], the son of Mary (n\u00e9e Harquail), who was from a \"prosperous family\", and Edwin Benedict Flaherty, an entrepreneur and chemist.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=cOSIAAAAMAAJ&q=%22Edwin+Benedict+Flaherty+and+Mary+Harquail+Flaherty%22&dq=%22Edwin+Benedict+Flaherty+and+Mary+Harquail+Flaherty%22 |title=The Canadian Parliamentary Guide - Gale Canada, Pierre G. Normandin - Google Books |publisher=Books.google.ca |date= |accessdate=April 10, 2014|isbn=9781896413433 |year=1997 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legacy.com/obituaries/montrealgazette/obituary.aspx?n=mary-harquail-flaherty&pid=117819420 |title=Mary Harquail Flaherty Obituary: View Mary Flaherty's Obituary by The Gazette |publisher=Legacy.com |date= |accessdate=April 10, 2014}}</ref> His parents were from [[New Brunswick]], his father from [[Loggieville, New Brunswick|Loggieville]] and his mother from [[Campbellton, New Brunswick|Campbellton]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fin.gc.ca/n12/12-143_1-eng.asp |title=Archived - Remarks by the Honourable Jim Flaherty, Minister of Finance, to the Fredericton Chamber of Commerce |publisher=Fin.gc.ca |date=November 13, 2012 |accessdate=April 10, 2014}}</ref> He was the sixth of eight children.<ref name=\"Jim Flaherty, 64, dies at Ottawa home one month after resigning as finance minister\"/> He attended Bishop Whelan High School and [[Loyola High School (Montreal)|Loyola High School, Montreal]]. Flaherty attended [[Princeton University]], where he received a [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree in sociology and graduated [[cum laude]] in 1970.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/rob-magazine/one-day-well-look-back-and-thank-jim-flaherty/article575748/?page=all |title=One day, we'll look back and thank Jim Flaherty |date=August 26, 2010 |first=Kevin |last=Carmichael |accessdate=April 11, 2014 |newspaper=The Globe and Mail }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.princeton.edu/canadian/history/CanadianStudiesAnnualReport2007-08.pdf |title=Annual Report for Academic Year 2007\u201308 |accessdate=April 11, 2014 |publisher=Princeton University |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130918201834/http://www.princeton.edu/canadian/history/CanadianStudiesAnnualReport2007-08.pdf |archivedate=September 18, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> He wrote his senior thesis on the sensitivity training at [[Camp X]], a military training institute in Ontario.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://dailyprincetonian.com/news/2014/04/news-and-notes-flaherty-70-former-canadian-finance-minister-dies-at-64/ |title=News and Notes: Flaherty \u201970, former Canadian finance minister, dies at 64 |newspaper=The Daily Princetonian |date=April 10, 2014 |accessdate=April 11, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140819065826/http://dailyprincetonian.com/news/2014/04/news-and-notes-flaherty-70-former-canadian-finance-minister-dies-at-64/ |archive-date=August 19, 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He then received a [[Bachelor of Laws]] degree from [[Osgoode Hall Law School]] of [[York University]].\n\nHe practised law for 20 years<ref>{{cite web|title=The Hon Jim Flaherty, PC, MP, MP--Whitby Oshawa|url=http://www.jimflahertymp.ca/jim-flaherty/about-jim|accessdate=February 24, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140228160726/http://www.jimflahertymp.ca/jim-flaherty/about-jim|archivedate=February 28, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref>  before formally entering politics in 1995. He was a founding partner of Flaherty Dow Elliott after splitting from Gilbert Wright and Flaherty. Flaherty Dow Elliott & McCarthy LLP, as it is now known, is a law firm specializing in motor vehicle accident and personal injury litigation.\n\n==Provincial politics==\nHe first ran for the [[Legislative Assembly of Ontario|Ontario legislature]] in the [[1990 Ontario general election|provincial election of 1990]], finishing third against [[Ontario New Democratic Party|New Democrat]] [[Drummond White]] and [[Ontario Liberal Party|Liberal]] [[Allan Furlong]] in the riding of [[Durham Centre (provincial electoral district)|Durham Centre]]. He ran again and was elected in the [[1995 Ontario general election|1995 election]].<ref name=\"20years=trinh\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/jim-flaherty-s-20-years-in-politics-1.2577577|title=Jim Flaherty's 20 years in politics|last=Theresa Do|first=Trinh|date=Mar 18, 2014|website=cbc.ca|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=Apr 10, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Cabinet===\nHe was named [[Ministry of Labour (Ontario)|Minister of Labour]] in the [[Cabinet (government)|cabinet]] of [[List of Ontario Premiers|Premier]] [[Mike Harris]] on October 10, 1997, and kept this position until after the [[1999 Ontario general election|1999 election]]. He also served as interim [[Solicitor General of Ontario|Solicitor General]] and [[Ministry of Correctional Services|Minister of Correctional Services]] from April 27 to July 27, 1998.<ref name=\"20years=trinh\" />\n\nFlaherty was re-elected in the [[1999 Ontario general election|1999 election]] in the redistributed riding of Whitby\u2013Ajax, and was named [[Attorney General of Ontario|Attorney General]] with responsibility for [[Ministry of Aboriginal Affairs (Ontario)|Native Affairs]] on June 17, 1999. On February 8, 2001, he was appointed [[Ministry of Finance (Ontario)|Minister of Finance]] and [[Deputy Premier of Ontario|Deputy Premier]]. He was a key promoter of tax credits for parents sending their children to private and denominational schools, which the Tories had campaigned against in 1999.<ref name=\"20years=trinh\" /> In June 2001, Flaherty was evicted from his constituency office in a theatrical action by [[Ontario Coalition Against Poverty]] which aimed to bring home the effects of his policies.<ref name=\"Deed\">{{cite journal |last1=Coulter |first1=Kendra |title=Solidarity in Deed: Poor People's Organizations, Unions, and the Politics of Antipoverty Work in Ontario |journal=Anthropology of Work Review |date=December 2012 |volume=33 |issue=2 |pages=101\u2013112 |doi=10.1111/j.1548-1417.2012.01083.x}}</ref>\n\n===2002 Ontario PC leadership bid===\nFlaherty ran to succeed Harris in the [[2002 Progressive Conservative Party of Ontario leadership election|2002 PC leadership election]], but lost to frontrunner [[Ernie Eves]], his predecessor as finance minister. Flaherty's campaign featured attacks on Eves, calling him a \"serial waffler\" and a \"pale, pink imitation of Dalton McGuinty\".<ref>[http://www.sesresearch.com/news/in_the_news/NationalPostJ31.pdf \"Flaherty gets personal with attack on Eves\"], ''[[National Post]]'', January 31, 2002</ref><ref name=\"20years=trinh\" />\n\nFlaherty's leadership campaign focused on \"law and order\" themes, and one of his proposals was to make [[homelessness]] illegal. His purported plan was to have special constables encourage homeless persons to seek out shelters or hospitals. He argued that his policy would save the lives of homeless persons; leadership rival [[Elizabeth Witmer]] and other critics described it as callous, and ineffective against the root causes of homelessness.<ref>{{cite news |title= Activist thought Flaherty joking |author= Heather Capannelli |page= A5 |newspaper= The Globe and Mail|date= February 16, 2002| publisher = via Proquest (subscription required) }}</ref><ref name=\"20years=trinh\" />\n\nFlaherty also promised to implement further [[tax cut]]s, carry through with plans to create a tax credit for parents sending their children to private school, and [[privatization|privatizing]] the [[Liquor Control Board of Ontario]]. Flaherty also emerged as a [[social conservative]] in this campaign, particularly a staunch stance against [[abortion]] and his association with [[anti-abortion]] groups. On April 15, 2002, Eves demoted him to the less-prominent position of Minister of Enterprise, Opportunity and Innovation. Flaherty retained this position until the Tories were defeated in the [[2003 Ontario general election|provincial election of 2003]]. Flaherty himself was re-elected by a reduced margin.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/ontariovotes2003/riding/096/ |title=Ontario Votes 2003: Whitby-Ajax |publisher=CBC.ca |date=2003-10-02 |accessdate=2014-04-11}}</ref><ref name=\"20years=trinh\" />\n\n===Opposition and 2004 Ontario PC leadership bid===\nFollowing the defeat of the Conservatives, Eves announced that he would resign as leader in 2004. Flaherty declared himself a candidate to succeed him, but was defeated by [[John Tory]] by a margin of 54 percent to 46 percent on the second ballot of the [[2004 Progressive Conservative Party of Ontario leadership election|PC leadership election]] held on September 18, 2004. His supporters included former cabinet ministers [[John Baird (Canadian politician)|John Baird]], [[Tim Hudak]] and [[Norm Sterling]].<ref name=\"20years=trinh\" /> His 2004 leadership campaign was similar to that of 2002. He emphasized [[Fiscal conservatism|fiscally conservative]] themes, including further tax cuts and greater privatization. He promised to create EXCEL scholarships, whereby students attaining high grades in high school would have half their university tuition paid by the government. Until 2005, Flaherty served as [[Shadow Cabinet|finance critic]] in [[John Tory]]'s shadow cabinet.<ref name=\"20years=trinh\" /><ref>{{cite news|author=Richard Mackie |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/flaherty-klees-win-key-roles-in-torys-shadow-cabinet/article1004880/ |title=Flaherty, Klees win key roles in Tory's shadow cabinet |newspaper=The Globe and Mail |accessdate=2014-04-11}}</ref>\n\n==Federal Finance Minister==\n[[File:Canadian Finance Minister Jim Flaherty and Irish President Mary McAleese.jpg|thumb|Flaherty stands behind Irish President [[Mary McAleese]]]]\n\nOn June 13, 2005, the Canadian news [[website]] bourque.org reported that a meeting of prominent Conservative organizers and fundraisers had been held to plan for a Flaherty bid for the leadership of the federal party should [[Stephen Harper]] resign.\nIn December 2005, the [[2006 Canadian federal election|2006 general election]] was called. Flaherty resigned his seat in the Ontario legislature to run for the [[Conservative Party of Canada]] in the riding of [[Whitby\u2014Oshawa]], narrowly unseating incumbent [[Judi Longfield]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/canadavotes2006/riding/206/ |title=Canada Votes 2006: Whitby-Oshawa |publisher=CBC.ca |date= |accessdate=2014-04-11}}</ref>\n\nFlaherty's wife, [[Christine Elliott]], won Flaherty's former provincial seat in a [[by-election]], defeating Longfield who was running as the [[Ontario Liberal Party|provincial Liberal]] candidate. This marked the first time in Canadian history that a husband and wife have simultaneously represented the same electoral district at two different levels of government.\n\nOn February 6, 2006, Flaherty was sworn in as [[Minister of Finance (Canada)|Minister of Finance]] in Stephen Harper's new Conservative [[Canadian Cabinet|Cabinet]].<ref>[http://www.canada.com/nationalpost/news/story.html?id=79e62b28-720f-461d-8820-da827d78406f 'Western Tories may miss out on Cabinet posts'] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160106235956/http://www.canada.com/nationalpost/news/story.html?id=79e62b28-720f-461d-8820-da827d78406f |date=January 6, 2016 }}, ''[[National Post]]'', January 16, 2006</ref>\nHe was also appointed Minister Responsible for the Greater Toronto Area. In his capacity as Minister of Finance, he served as a Governor of the World Bank and the International Monetary Fund.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jimflahertymp.ca/jim-flaherty/about-jim |title=About Jim |publisher=Jimflahertymp.ca |accessdate=April 10, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140228160726/http://www.jimflahertymp.ca/jim-flaherty/about-jim |archivedate=February 28, 2014 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nHe announced his resignation from the cabinet on March 18, 2014.<ref>{{cite news |title=Jim Flaherty resigns post as Finance Minister; Joe Oliver to replace him, sources say |url=https://nationalpost.com/news/politics/finance-minister-jim-flaherty-resigns |accessdate=January 30, 2019 |work=[[National Post]] |date=March 18, 2014 |language=en-CA}}</ref>\n\n===October 31, 2006, income trust announcement===\nFlaherty was a central figure in the debate surrounding the [[Income trust#The Conservatives propose new rules for income trusts|new proposed rules for taxation of Canadian income trusts]]. His announcement on October 31, 2006 of a rule change to tax [[income trust]]s levelled the playing field between forms of business such that businesses operating as income trusts no longer enjoyed a tax advantage over businesses operating as corporations.  The announcement was accompanied by a further planned reduction in the corporate rate so that the two moves together were not expected to generate additional revenue for the government.\n\nFlaherty said that income trusts would cost the government $500 million annually in lost tax revenue and shift the burden onto ordinary people.<ref>{{cite news | author = ''[[Global National]]'' | title = Exclusive: Flaherty received death threats | publisher = Global National TV | url = http://www.canada.com/globaltv/national/story.html?id=539d04fe-471d-4cfa-9fc6-af81edc7e085 | date = February 1, 2007 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070325125029/http://www.canada.com/globaltv/national/story.html?id=539d04fe-471d-4cfa-9fc6-af81edc7e085 | archivedate = March 25, 2007 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> The Canadian Association of Income Trust Investors said that foreign takeovers of Canadian income trusts have had the opposite effect and caused decrease in federal government tax revenues.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://caiti-online-media.blogspot.com/2007/09/primewest-energy-trust-bought-for.html |title=Primewest Energy Trust -Bought for Nothing Down & No Income Taxes |publisher=Caiti-online-media.blogspot.com |date=September 27, 2007 |accessdate=April 10, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://network.nationalpost.com/np/blogs/francis/archive/2007/10/01/takeovers-income-trust.aspx |title=Canada Under {{sic{{!}}Se{{!}}ige{{!}}hide=y}}: Thanks Harper and Flaherty |access-date=January 4, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071224034853/http://network.nationalpost.com/np/blogs/francis/archive/2007/10/01/takeovers-income-trust.aspx |archive-date=December 24, 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n[[Diane Francis]], editor-at-large for the ''[[National Post]]'', urged that the rule changes be recanted, arguing that there were flaws in the policy which hurt ordinary, hard-working Canadian investors.<ref>{{cite news | author = Diane Francis | title = Trusts proposal must be recanted | publisher = Financial Post | url = http://www.caiti.info/resources/diane_francis_articles.pdf |format=PDF| date = December 9, 2006 }}</ref>\n\nSpecial hearings by the House of Commons Standing Committee on Finance commenced January 30, 2007. [[John McCallum]], the Liberal finance critic, asked Flaherty to explain the reasoning behind the change in income trust tax policy. McCallum said \"Your first problem is that having lured hundreds of thousands of ordinary Canadians into income trusts by promising not to raise taxes you then cut them off at the knees.\"<ref>{{cite news | author = John MacCallum | title = Your first problem is that having lured hundreds of thousands of ordinary Canadians into income trusts by promising not to raise taxes you then cut them off at the knees | newspaper = National Post | url = http://www.caiti.info/resources/john_mccallum_op_ed.pdf |format=PDF| date = January 3, 2007 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | author = CAITI | title = Mr. Harper Is this what you mean by Transparency? | publisher = CAITI | url = http://www.caiti.info/resources/redacted.pdf |format=PDF| date = February 8, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nOn February 28, 2007, the committee released their report, ''Taxing Income Trusts: Reconcilable or Irreconcilable differences?'', recommending a reduction of the proposed tax to 10 percent from 31.5 percent.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.caiti.info/resources/income_trust_report.pdf |title=Taxing Income Trusts: Reconcilable or Irreconcilable differences? (application/pdf Object) |publisher=www.caiti.info |accessdate=September 16, 2010 }}</ref>\n\n====Fullard opposition====\nOn August 21, 2008, Brent Fullard, president of the Canadian Association of Income Trust Investors, challenged Flaherty to debate supposed tax leakage associated with income trusts. Fullard announced he would put up $50,000, payable to his favourite charity. Given the minister's \"current crusade on financial literacy\", Fullard believed a suitable charitable cause would be a scholarship for business education. \"By doing this we could help repair the damage caused by the Minister's statement that Ontario is the last place to invest.\"<ref>{{cite web|first1=Barry|last1=Critchley|title=Flaherty's $50,000 challenge|accessdate=2014-04-13|year=2008|publisher=[[Financial Post]]|website=financialpost.com|url=http://www.financialpost.com/analysis/columnists/story.html?id=67793cff-2765-40f4-b7c4-da81bc190f09|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140414110955/http://www.financialpost.com/analysis/columnists/story.html?id=67793cff-2765-40f4-b7c4-da81bc190f09|archivedate=April 14, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Flaherty turned down the request. \"The tax fairness plan is law. The Minister made his position clear before the finance committee and there is no need for further debate,\" according to his press spokesperson.<ref>{{cite web\n| first1 = Barry\n| last1 = Critchley\n| title = A tale of two documents\n| accessdate = 2014-04-13\n| date = August 22, 2008\n| publisher = [[Financial Post]]\n| website = financialpost.com\n| url = http://www.financialpost.com/scripts/story.html?id=23b64120-93fc-4783-84f6-3b70d3a7f0fd&k=97729\n| url-status = dead\n| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140414121015/http://www.financialpost.com/scripts/story.html?id=23b64120-93fc-4783-84f6-3b70d3a7f0fd&k=97729\n| archivedate = April 14, 2014\n| df = mdy-all\n}}</ref>\n\n===Registered Disability Savings Plan===\nIn Budget 2007, Flaherty introduced the [[Registered Disability Savings Plan]] (RDSP). The RDSP is a long-term savings plan to help Canadians with disabilities and their families save.<ref>{{cite news |last=Galloway |first=Gloria |date=10 April 2014 |title=10 major moments in Flaherty\u2019s finance tenure |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/10-major-moments-in-flahertys-finance-tenure/article17924986/ |newspaper=The Globe and Mail |location=Toronto ON |publisher= |accessdate=10 April 2014 }}</ref> The RDSP resembles its other saving counterparts, the RRSP and the RESP, and is meant to ensure a secure future for people with disabilities. The Government assists these families by contributing through grants and bonds that supplement contributions.<ref name=\"servicecanada1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.servicecanada.gc.ca/eng/goc/rdsp.shtml |title=Registered Disability Savings Plan |publisher=Service Canada |accessdate=10 April 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Tax-Free Savings Account===\nIn Budget 2008, Flaherty introduced the [[Tax-Free Savings Account]] (TFSA), a flexible, registered, general-purpose savings vehicle that allows Canadians to earn tax-free investment income to more easily meet lifetime savings needs.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tfsa.gc.ca/ |title=Tax-Free Savings Account |publisher=Government of Canada |accessdate=10 April 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140517040846/http://tfsa.gc.ca/ |archivedate=May 17, 2014 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe measure, which came into effect on January 2, 2009, has clear differences with the Registered Retirement Savings Plan (RRSP). There is a tax deduction for contributions to an RRSP, and withdrawals of contributions and investment income are all taxable. In contrast, there are no tax deductions for contributions to a TFSA. Beginning in 2013, contribution room in the TFSA has increased to $5,500 per calendar year. The Canada Revenue Agency describes the difference between the TFSA and an RRSP as follows: \"An RRSP is primarily intended for retirement. The TFSA is like an RRSP for everything else in your life.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Boggs |first=Talbot |date= 22 February 2012 |title=Consider both RRSPs and TFSAs  |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/globe-investor/personal-finance/consider-both-rrsps-and-tfsas/article548181/ |newspaper=The Globe and Mail |location=Toronto ON |publisher= |accessdate= 10 April 2014}}</ref>\n\nFlaherty's measure was supported by many organizations, including the [[C.D. Howe Institute]], which stated: \"This tax policy gem is very good news for Canadians, and Mr. Flaherty and his government deserve credit for a novel program.\"<ref>{{cite news |title= TFSAs: the biggest thing since RRSPs |author= Finn Poschmann |page= FP18 |newspaper= National Post |date= February 27, 2008| publisher = }}</ref>\n\n===EUROMoney Magazine ===\nIn 2009, Flaherty received an award from EUROMoney Magazine, naming him [[Euromoney Finance Minister of the Year|Finance Minister of the Year]]. Flaherty is the first Canadian to hold this honour. It says he \"enhanced his country's reputation for sound fiscal policy that takes full account of social justice, while a strong regulatory regime has kept the financial sector out of the chaos.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.euromoney.com/Article/2297318/Finance-minister-of-the-year-Jim-Flaherty-Canada.html |title=Banking industry news & analysis of international finance &#124; Euromoney magazine |publisher=Euromoney.com |date= |accessdate=April 10, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Federation of Canadian Municipalities report on infrastructure===\n\nFlaherty responded to a report from the [[Federation of Canadian Municipalities]] that suggested that cities had an infrastructure deficit of $123 billion and the federal government should step up with some cash with the suggestion cities should stop \"whining\" and repair their own crumbling infrastructure.\n\n[[Calgary]] Mayor [[Dave Bronconnier]] claimed Flaherty sidestepped responsibility for billions in infrastructure dollars being sought, when Flaherty advised municipalities to \"do their job\" because the feds are \"not in the pothole business\". \"Let\u2019s get on with the job and stop complaining about it and do their job\", Flaherty continued, noting the Building Canada fund will inject $33 billion into cities to help deal with the infrastructure crunch. However Bronconnier said the plan is merely a \"repackaging\" of a number of pre-existing funding arrangements.<ref>{{cite web\n |url          = http://www.dcnonl.com/article/id25251\n |title        = Calgary mayor keeps hard hat and shovel at the ready for Jim Flaherty\n |publisher    = Daily Commercial News and Construction Record\n |accessdate   = February 21, 2008\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20080311102632/http://www.dcnonl.com/article/id25251\n |archive-date = March 11, 2008\n |url-status     = dead\n |df           = mdy-all\n}}</ref> The Building Canada Fund was strongly criticized for being designed to fail, due to excessive red tape, which has delayed much of the funding from being awarded.<ref>\n{{cite web |url=http://www2.canada.com/reginaleaderpost/news/viewpoints/story.html?id=0186111b-896d-469b-b0f6-43346a03fd3c&p=1 |title=Watch the fine print in Tory promises |accessdate=2014-04-13 |last1=Mandryk |website=canada.com |publisher=[[Postmedia News]] |first1=Murray |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140414063135/http://www2.canada.com/reginaleaderpost/news/viewpoints/story.html?id=0186111b-896d-469b-b0f6-43346a03fd3c&p=1 |archivedate=April 14, 2014 |df=mdy-all }} \n</ref>\n\n[[Mississauga]] Mayor [[Hazel McCallion]] went further by issuing a challenge to Flaherty to publicly debate the need for permanent federal funding for the repair and upkeep of municipal roads and bridges. McCallion said \"Flaherty has stated in the media that some of the municipalities have not kept up with infrastructure and did not establish adequate reserves. Well, I can tell him that he is dead wrong. The facts are that Mississauga has carefully set aside reserves for infrastructure for years.\" McCallion noted that cities are trying to maintain 58 per cent of public infrastructure with eight cents of every tax dollar.<ref>\n{{cite web\n|url=http://www.mississauganews.com/article/10479\n|title=Hazel calls out the Finance Minister - The Mississauga News - Mississauga.com\n|publisher=www.mississauganews.com\n|accessdate=February 21, 2008\n|last=Chin\n|first=Joe\n}}\n</ref> Flaherty did not accept Hazel McCallion's offer to debate.<ref>\n{{cite news\n|url=https://www.thestar.com/opinion/columnists/2008/01/25/in_this_corner_a_tory_minister_wearing_blinders.html\n|title=In this corner, a Tory minister wearing blinders\n|publisher=www.thestar.com\n|accessdate=February 21, 2008\n|last=Hume\n|first=Christopher\n| location=Toronto\n| date=January 25, 2008\n}}\n</ref>\n\n===Department of Finance contracts questioned===\nFlaherty said his office broke government contracting rules in hiring MacPhie & Company to help write the 2007 budget speech and provide advice on how to sell the document. MacPhie & Company was awarded the $122,000 contract without tender by Flaherty's office.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://canadianpress.google.com/article/ALeqM5icnUoJmXDHEK4LdEVO1eZYb3ir1g |title=The Canadian Press: Opposition asks for reviews of contract to Flaherty speech writer |publisher=canadianpress.google.com |accessdate=2008-02-01 |last= |first= }}{{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> On February 7, 2008, Liberal finance critic [[John McCallum]] formally called on [[Auditor General of Canada|Auditor General]] [[Sheila Fraser]] to conduct an audit into the untendered contract awarded by Flaherty to MacPhie & Company for work done in advance of the 2007 budget.<ref name=\"brennan1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/News/Canada/article/303484#|title=  Flaherty contracts questioned|work=TheStar|accessdate=February 14, 2008|last=Brennan|first=Richard| location=Toronto| date=February 14, 2008}}</ref>\n\nThe ''[[Toronto Star]]'' determined that several people who supported Flaherty when he was an [[Executive Council of Ontario|Ontario cabinet]] minister or who supported his two failed bids to lead the Ontario Tories were awarded employment contracts or given appointments.<ref name=\"brennan1\"/> The employment contracts awarded were under the $25,000 Treasury Board contract bidding limit. Bronwen Evans received a $24,877.50 contract to write speeches for Flaherty from June 2006 until last February.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.fin.gc.ca/scripts/contracts-contrats/reports-rapports-eng.asp?r=c&refNum=6007612A&q=1&yr=2006\n |title=Disclosure of Contracts Over $10,000\n |work=fin.gc.ca\n |accessdate=October 17, 2010\n}}</ref> David Curtain, who worked on Flaherty's Ontario leadership campaign, received $24,877.50 to write the finance minister's first budget speech. Curtain was also paid $3,350 to write a keynote address earlier in 2008 for Flaherty. Lawyer James Love, who donated $63,000 to Flaherty over two leadership campaigns, was appointed to the Royal Canadian Mint. Another Flaherty donor, Carol Hansell, was appointed to the board of directors of the [[Bank of Canada]] in October 2006. Toronto family law lawyer Sara Beth Mintz, an Ontario Progressive Conservative Party vice-president, received $24,900 for budget \"analysis, assessment and advice\".<ref>{{cite web\n |url= http://www.fin.gc.ca/scripts/contracts-contrats/reports-rapports-eng.asp?r=c&refNum=6008932&q=4&yr=2006\n |title=Disclosure of Contracts Over $10,000\n |work=fin.gc.ca\n |accessdate=October 17, 2010\n}}</ref> MacPhie & Company also got another contract for $24,645 for work done on Advantage Canada, a long-term, national economic plan.<ref>{{cite web\n |url= http://www.fin.gc.ca/scripts/contracts-contrats/reports-rapports-eng.asp?r=c&refNum=6008331&q=3&yr=2006\n |title=Disclosure of Contracts Over $10,000\n |work=fin.gc.ca\n |accessdate=October 17, 2010\n}}</ref> Opposition parties said they were suspicious that contracts were coming in just under $25,000 in order to give business to Flaherty's friends and supporters.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=https://www.thestar.com/News/Canada/article/303484#|title=  Flaherty contracts questioned\n|work=TheStar|accessdate=February 14, 2008|last=Brennan|first=Richard| location=Toronto| date=February 14, 2008}}</ref>\n\nOn May 13, 2008, Flaherty appeared before the Public Accounts committee, facing questions about multiple sole-sourced contracts worth more than $300,000 that were given by the government.<ref>\n{{cite news\n|url=https://nationalpost.com/news/canada/story.html?id=512600\n|archive-url=https://archive.is/20080516005636/http://www.nationalpost.com/news/canada/story.html?id=512600\n|url-status=dead\n|archive-date=May 16, 2008\n|title=Flaherty grilled over untendered communications contracts\n|newspaper=National Post\n|accessdate=May 13, 2008\n|last=Fitzpatrick\n|first=Meagan\n}}\n</ref> Flaherty says he was unaware his former chief of staff broke government rules in handing a well-connected Tory an untendered contract to write the 2007 budget speech.<ref>\n{{cite web\n|url=http://canadianpress.google.com/article/ALeqM5hC85lSgl9cX-zg9HGBYbVu2QIBaQ\n|title=The Canadian Press: Flaherty says unaware $122,000 speech contract to supporter improper\n|publisher=Canadian Press\n|accessdate=May 13, 2008\n|last=\n|first=\n}}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url          = http://www.disclosed.ca/?keyword=MacPhie\n |title        = Disclosed: Search results for MacPhie\n |work         = disclosed.ca\n |accessdate   = October 17, 2010\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110706175245/http://www.disclosed.ca/?keyword=MacPhie\n |archive-date = July 6, 2011\n |url-status     = dead\n |df           = mdy-all\n}}</ref>\n\n===Foreign Account Tax Compliance Act===\nThe Foreign Account Tax Compliance Act is American legislation that requires cooperation, legal and financial, from Canada (and other nations), in order to be implemented. The official reason given for this legislation was efforts to crack down on tax evasion. However, in a letter Flaherty sent to U.S. newspapers in September 2011, he said the law would waste resources  and raise privacy concerns.  On February 5, 2014, Flaherty signed Canada on as a participant to FATCA through an [[FATCA agreement between Canada and the United States|Intergovernmental Agreement]] (IGA).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/fatca-facts-what-canadians-need-to-know-about-new-u-s-tax-law-1.2493882 |title=FATCA facts: What Canadians need to know about new U.S. tax law - Canada - CBC News |publisher=Cbc.ca |date= |accessdate=April 10, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Abolishing the penny===\nWhile announcing Economic Action Plan 2012 on March 29 in the House of Commons, Flaherty explained that, by February 2013, the government would be phasing out the penny. The cost to produce each new penny was 1.6 cents, which exceeded the penny's face value by 0.6 cents. The estimated savings for taxpayers from phasing out the penny is about $11 million a year. Even though the government eliminated the penny from circulation, Canadians can continue to use pennies for cash transactions indefinitely for businesses that choose to accept them or they can redeem rolled pennies at their financial institutions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fin.gc.ca/1cent/toolkit-boite-a-outils-eng.asp |title=Toolkit for Businesses: Phasing out the Penny |publisher=Fin.gc.ca |date= |accessdate=April 10, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.nationalpost.com/2012/03/30/canada-penny-federal-budget-one-cent-coin/ |title=Canadian penny drops in federal budget as Jim Flaherty signals end of one cent coin &#124; National Post |publisher=News.nationalpost.com |date= |accessdate=April 10, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Building Canada Plan===\nOn May 21, 2013, Flaherty introduced his 2013 Budget. The Budget contained a new Building Canada Plan for the construction of public infrastructure such as roads, bridges, transit and port facilities.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.journalofcommerce.com/article/id54666/profenvironmental |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130426233847/http://www.journalofcommerce.com/article/id54666/profenvironmental |url-status=dead |archive-date=April 26, 2013 |title=Building Canada Plan maps infrastructure spending \u2013 Journal of Commerce |publisher=Journalofcommerce.com |accessdate=April 10, 2014 }}</ref> The plan provides $53 billion in investments to support local and economic infrastructure projects, including more than $47 billion in new funding over 10 years, starting in 2014\u20132015.<ref>{{cite web |author=Diane Crocker Published on |url=http://www.thewesternstar.com/News/Local/2013-03-22/article-3205324/Greeley-pleased-to-see-new-Building-Canada-plan-in-federal-budget/1 |title=Greeley pleased to see new Building Canada plan in federal budget - Local |publisher=The Western Star |accessdate=April 10, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130802192839/http://www.thewesternstar.com/News/Local/2013-03-22/article-3205324/Greeley-pleased-to-see-new-Building-Canada-plan-in-federal-budget/1 |archivedate=August 2, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Budgets presented===\nFlaherty presented nine budgets to the Canadian Parliament as Minister of Finance.\n* [[2006 Canadian federal budget]]\n* [[2007 Canadian federal budget]]\n* [[2008 Canadian federal budget]]\n* [[2009 Canadian federal budget]]\n* [[2010 Canadian federal budget]]\n* [[2011 Canadian federal budget]] (presented in March 2011 and again in June).\n* [[2012 Canadian federal budget]]\n* [[2013 Canadian federal budget]]\n* [[2014 Canadian federal budget]]\n\n===Resignation from Cabinet===\nOn March 18, 2014, Flaherty announced that he was resigning as Minister of Finance in order to return to the private sector. While he had openly discussed health challenges associated with managing [[bullous pemphigoid]], including taking prescription steroids, he said the decision was reached after many months of consultation with his family and that his health was not a factor in his decision.<ref>{{cite news|author=Steven Chase |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/i-dont-like-talking-about-this-flaherty-on-battle-with-skin-disease/article8025398/#dashboard/follows/ |title='I don't like talking about this:' Flaherty on battle with skin disease |newspaper=The Globe and Mail |date=January 31, 2013 |accessdate=April 10, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Canada |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/read-jim-flahertys-statement-on-resigning-as-finance-minister/article17551462/#dashboard/follows/ |title=Read Jim Flaherty's statement on resigning as finance minister |newspaper=The Globe and Mail |date=March 18, 2014 |accessdate=April 10, 2014}}</ref> Flaherty continued sitting in the House of Commons as an MP until his death three weeks later.<ref name=\"Jim Flaherty, 64, dies at Ottawa home one month after resigning as finance minister\"/><ref>{{cite news|title=Joe Oliver takes over federal finance portfoliot|url=http://www.ctvnews.ca/politics/joe-oliver-takes-over-federal-finance-portfolio-1.1735916|accessdate=March 19, 2014|newspaper=CTV News|date=March 19, 2014}}</ref>\nAt the time of his resignation, he had been the honour of being the ''Longest continuous serving cabinet minister in a single portfolio'' in the 28th Canadian Ministry.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.parl.gc.ca/Parlinfo/Files/Parliamentarian.aspx?Item=95e9d5a2-e9a6-4037-b6a7-218bfdc01a33&Language=E| accessdate=April 12, 2014|title=PARLINFO - Parliamentarian File - Federal Experience - FLAHERTY, The Hon. James Michael (Jim), P.C., B.A., LL.B.|website=parl.gc.ca}}</ref>\n\n===Honours===\nAn office building in [[Ottawa]], housing employees from the [[Department of Finance (Canada)|Department of Finance]], is named after Flaherty.<ref>https://ottawacitizen.com/news/politics/new-finance-canada-building-named-after-jim-flaherty</ref>\n\nWith the [[2017 Canada Day Honours]], Flaherty was awarded with a posthumous [[Meritorious Service Cross]].<ref name=\"canadagazette.gc.ca\">http://canadagazette.gc.ca/rp-pr/p1/2017/2017-07-01/html/gh-rg-eng.html</ref>\n<center>\n[[File:MSC ribbon-civil.png|100px]][[File:QEII Golden Jubilee Medal ribbon.png|100px]][[File:QEII Diamond Jubilee Medal ribbon.png|100px]]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:silver;\" align=\"center\"\n|Ribbon || Description || Notes\n|-\n|[[File:MSC ribbon-civil.png|100px]] || [[Meritorious Service Cross]]||\n* 2017: Christine Elliott and the late Jim Flaherty founded Abilities Centre, a unique, world-class facility in Whitby that engages people of all ages and abilities in sports, the arts and personal growth activities. Thanks to their dedicated support, the centre has become a local and international example of inclusiveness where everyone can participate equally.<ref>https://www.gg.ca/en/honours/recipients/136-52994</ref><ref name=\"canadagazette.gc.ca\">http://canadagazette.gc.ca/rp-pr/p1/2017/2017-07-01/html/gh-rg-eng.html</ref>\n|-\n|[[File:QEII Golden Jubilee Medal ribbon.png|100px]] || [[Queen Elizabeth II Golden Jubilee Medal]] for Canada||\n* 2002:<ref>https://www.gg.ca/en/honours/recipients/125-32011</ref>\n|-\n|[[File:QEII Diamond Jubilee Medal ribbon.png|100px]] || [[Queen Elizabeth II Diamond Jubilee Medal]] for Canada||\n* 2012: As the [[Minister of the Crown]] and as an elected Member of the [[House of Commons of Canada]], The Honourable James M. Flaherty was awarded the medal as a member of the [[Canadian order of precedence]].<ref>https://www.gg.ca/en/honours/recipients/126-685</ref>\n|-\n\n|}\n</center>\n\n==Personal life and death==\n[[File:Flaherty state funeral DSC 0105 (13905494015).jpg|thumb|right|Media overlooking a crowd fronting the [[Cathedral Church of St. James (Toronto)|Cathedral Church of St. James]] in Toronto during Flaherty's state funeral on 16 April 2014]]\n\nFlaherty grew up in a [[Roman Catholic|Catholic]] family in [[Montreal]], and was of part [[Irish people|Irish]] descent. As a youth he was an avid [[Ice hockey|hockey]] player and won a hockey scholarship to [[Princeton University]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Perkins|first=Tara|title=Jim Flaherty: Time off the hustings, tucking into soup|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/careers/careers-leadership/jim-flaherty-time-off-the-hustings-tucking-into-soup/article576562/?page=all|newspaper=The Globe and Mail|date=April 8, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"vallance2002\">{{cite news|last=Vallance-Jones|first=Fred|title=1960s frustrating era for young Jim Flaherty|newspaper=The Spectator (Hamilton, Ontario)|page = A01|date=March 20, 2002}}</ref>\n\nThose familiar with Flaherty's work as a lawyer noted his dogged determination and a strong work ethic. One colleague,  Hamilton lawyer John Soule said, \"He is a driven person&nbsp;... and certainly is prepared to do what is necessary in terms of time and hard work to achieve what he believes is right\".<ref name=\"vallance2002\"/>  He assisted in several volunteer causes, including being the president of the Head Injury Association of Durham Region in Ontario.<ref name=\"vallance2002\"/>\n\nHis wife, Christine Elliott, was the [[Progressive Conservative Party of Ontario|Progressive Conservative]] Member of Provincial Parliament for Oshawa&ndash;Whitby, east of Toronto and Deputy Leader of the Opposition until her resignation in August 2015. The couple lived in Whitby and have triplet sons John, Gaelen and Quinn, who were born in 1991.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.thestar.com/moneyville/article/870692 | title = Daw: 4 tips Jim Flaherty is giving his three sons| publisher = Toronto Star (Moneyville) | date = October 4, 2010}}</ref> Her son Galen, used to work for Doug Ford, then [[Etobicoke]] councillor.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/toronto/a-young-flaherty-joins-doug-fords-staff/article598347/|title=A young Flaherty joins Doug Ford's staff|access-date=2018-02-28}}</ref>    Elliott and Flaherty have both championed issues surrounding children with disabilities; their son, John, has a disability.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2014/04/10/jim_flaherty_and_christine_elliott_were_partners_in_life_law_and_politics.html|title=Jim Flaherty and Christine Elliott were partners in life, law, and politics|newspaper=The Toronto Star|author=Robert Benzie|date=2014-10-04}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2013, Flaherty announced he had [[bullous pemphigoid]].<ref name=passes>[http://globalnews.ca/news/1263247/jim-flaherty-passes-away-at-63-reports/ Jim Flaherty passes away at 64], by Erika Tucker, at Global News; published April 10, 2014; retrieved April 10, 2014</ref> He was treated with [[prednisone]].<ref name = \"Boesveld2014\">{{cite news|author = Sarah Boesveld|title = Treatments that suppressed Jim Flaherty\u2019s rare skin disorder had a tremendous effect on him|url = http://news.nationalpost.com/2014/04/10/treatments-that-suppressed-jim-flahertys-rare-skin-disorder-had-a-tremendous-effect-on-him/|newspaper = [[National Post]]|date = April 10, 2014}}</ref> Flaherty died on April 10, 2014, at his home in Ottawa after suffering a heart attack at the age of 64.<ref name=dead>{{cite news|title=Former finance minister Jim Flaherty is dead at 64|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/flaherty/article17919447/|accessdate=April 10, 2014|newspaper=The Globe and Mail|date=April 10, 2014}}</ref>\n\nA [[State funerals in Canada|state funeral]] was held for Flaherty on April 16, 2014, at [[Cathedral Church of St. James (Toronto)|St. James Cathedral]] in Toronto.<ref>{{cite web|author = Laura Peyton|title = Jim Flaherty to have state funeral Wednesday|url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/jim-flaherty-to-have-state-funeral-wednesday-1.2607292|publisher = [[CBC News]]|date = April 11, 2014}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=40em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110810120708/http://www.jimflahertymp.ca/ Jim Flaherty MP] official site\n*{{Canadian Parliament links| parliament = 170343 | parlinfo = 2225 | openparl = jim-flaherty }}\n*{{Ontario MPP biography|ID=35}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{Canadian cabinet member navigational box header |ministry=Mike_Harris}}\n{{ministry box cabinet posts\n| post4preceded = [[Elizabeth Witmer]]\n| post4         = [[Ministry of Labour (Ontario)|Minister of Labour]]\n| post4years    = 1997\u20131999\n| post4note     =\n| post4followed = [[Chris Stockwell]]\n| post3preceded = [[Charles Harnick]]\n| post3         = [[List of Ontario Attorneys General|Attorney General]]\n| post3years    = 1999\u20132001\n| post3note     =\n| post3followed = [[David Young (Ontario politician)|David Young]]\n| post2preceded = [[Ernie Eves]]\n| post2         = [[Deputy Premier of Ontario]]\n| post2years    = 2001\u20132002\n| post2note     =\n| post2followed = [[Elizabeth Witmer]]\n| post1preceded = [[Ernie Eves]]\n| post1         = [[Ministry of Finance (Ontario)|Minister of Finance]]\n| post1years    = 2001\u20132002\n| post1note     =\n| post1followed = [[Janet Ecker]]\n}}\n{{ministry box special cabinet\n| post1preceded = [[Charles Harnick]]\n| post1         = [[Ministry of Aboriginal Affairs (Ontario)|Minister of Aboriginal Affairs]]\n| post1years    = 1999\u20132001\n| post1note     =\n| post1followed = [[David Young (Ontario politician)|David Young]]\n}}\n{{Canadian cabinet member navigational box header |ministry=Ernie_Eves}}\n{{ministry box cabinet posts\n| post1preceded = Position established\n| post1         = [[Minister of Enterprise, Opportunity and Innovation]]\n| post1years    = 2002\u20132003\n| post1note     =\n| post1followed = Position abolished\n}}\n{{Canadian federal ministry navigational box header |ministry=28}}\n{{ministry box cabinet posts\n| post1         = [[Minister of Finance (Canada)|Minister of Finance]]\n| post1years    = 2006\u20132014\n| post1note     =\n| post1preceded = [[Ralph Goodale]]\n| post1followed = [[Joe Oliver (politician)|Joe Oliver]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Harper Ministry}}\n{{Harris Ministry}}\n{{CanMinFinance}}\n{{Ontario Attorneys General}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Flaherty, Jim}}\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:2014 deaths]]\n[[Category:Anglophone Quebec people]]\n[[Category:Attorneys General of Ontario]]\n[[Category:Canadian Ministers of Finance]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:Quebec people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party of Canada MPs]]\n[[Category:Deputy premiers of Ontario]]\n[[Category:Finance ministers of Ontario]]\n[[Category:Lawyers in Ontario]]\n[[Category:Members of the House of Commons of Canada from Ontario]]\n[[Category:Members of the Queen's Privy Council for Canada]]\n[[Category:Osgoode Hall Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Lachine, Quebec]]\n[[Category:People from Whitby, Ontario]]\n[[Category:Princeton Tigers men's ice hockey players]]\n[[Category:Princeton University alumni]]\n[[Category:Progressive Conservative Party of Ontario MPPs]]\n[[Category:Members of the 28th Canadian Ministry]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2014}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix = [[The Honourable]]\n|birthname        = James Michael Flaherty\n|honorific-suffix = [[Queen's Privy Council for Canada|PC]], [[Meritorious Service Cross|MSC]]<ref name=\"canadagazette.gc.ca\">http://canadagazette.gc.ca/rp-pr/p1/2017/2017-07-01/html/gh-rg-eng.html</ref>  \n|image            = Jim Flaherty 2007.JPG\n\n|office           = [[Minister of Finance (Canada)|Minister of Finance]]\n|primeminister    = [[Stephen Harper]]\n|term_start       = February 6, 2006\n|term_end         = March 18, 2014\n|predecessor      = [[Ralph Goodale]]\n|successor        = [[Joe Oliver (politician)|Joe Oliver]]\n\n|constituency_MP1 = [[Whitby\u2014Oshawa|Whitby-Oshawa]]\n|parliament1      = Canadian\n|term_start1      = January 23, 2006\n|term_end1        = April 10, 2014\n|predecessor1     = [[Judi Longfield]]\n|successor1       = [[Pat Perkins]]\n\n|office2          = 6th [[Deputy Premier of Ontario]]\n|term_start2      = February 8, 2001\n|term_end2        = April 14, 2002\n|premier2         = [[Mike Harris]]\n|predecessor2     = [[Ernie Eves]]\n|successor2       = [[Elizabeth Witmer]]\n\n|office3          = [[Member of Provincial Parliament (Ontario)|Ontario MPP]]\n|term_start3      = 1999\n|term_end3        = 2005\n|predecessor3     = ''New riding''\n|successor3       = [[Christine Elliott]]\n|constituency3    = [[Whitby\u2014Ajax|Whitby-Ajax]]\n\n|term_start4      = 1995\n|term_end4        = 1999\n|predecessor4     = [[Drummond White]]\n|successor4       = ''Riding abolished''\n|constituency4    = [[Durham Centre (provincial electoral district)|Durham Centre]]\n\n|birth_date       = {{birth date|1949|12|30|mf=y}}\n|birth_place      = [[Lachine, Quebec]], Canada\n|death_date       = {{death date and age|2014|04|10|1949|12|30|mf=yes}}\n|death_place      = [[Ottawa|Ottawa, Ontario]], Canada\n|party            = [[Conservative Party of Canada|Conservative Party]]\n|spouse           = [[Christine Elliott]] {{small|(1986\u20132014)}}\n|children         = 3\n|alma_mater       = [[Princeton University]]<br />[[Osgoode Hall Law School|York University]]\n}}\n'''James Michael Flaherty''', {{Post-nominals|country=CAN|PC|MSC}} (December 30, 1949 \u2013 April 10, 2014) was a Canadian politician who served as [[Canada]]'s [[Minister of Finance (Canada)|federal Minister of Finance]] (2006\u20132014) and a [[Ministry of Finance (Ontario)|provincial Minister of Finance]] for [[Ontario]] (2001\u20132002). From 1995 until 2005, he was the [[Member of Provincial Parliament (Ontario)|Member of Provincial Parliament]] for [[Whitby\u2014Ajax]], and a member of the [[Progressive Conservative Party of Ontario|Ontario Progressive Conservative Party]] caucus and unsuccessfully sought the leadership of the provincial party on two occasions.\n\nFlaherty won the riding of [[Whitby\u2014Oshawa]] in the [[2006 Canadian federal election|federal election]] held January 23, 2006, as a member of the [[Conservative Party of Canada]] narrowly beating [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]] incumbent [[Judi Longfield]]. He was re-elected in [[2008 Canadian federal election|2008]] and [[2011 Canadian federal election|2011]]. Flaherty's widow, [[Christine Elliott]], is currently the [[Deputy Premier of Ontario]].\n\n==Education and early career==\nFlaherty was born on December 30, 1949<ref name=\"Jim Flaherty, 64, dies at Ottawa home one month after resigning as finance minister\">{{cite news|title=Jim Flaherty, 64, dies at Ottawa home one month after resigning as finance minister|url=http://news.nationalpost.com/2014/04/10/jim-flaherty-has-died-sources-say-paramedics-outside-former-finance-minsters-condo/|accessdate=April 10, 2014|newspaper=National Post|date=April 10, 2014|author=National Post staff|author2=Postmedia News}}</ref> in [[Lachine, Quebec]], the son of Mary (n\u00e9e Harquail), who was from a \"prosperous family\", and Edwin Benedict Flaherty, an entrepreneur and chemist.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=cOSIAAAAMAAJ&q=%22Edwin+Benedict+Flaherty+and+Mary+Harquail+Flaherty%22&dq=%22Edwin+Benedict+Flaherty+and+Mary+Harquail+Flaherty%22 |title=The Canadian Parliamentary Guide - Gale Canada, Pierre G. Normandin - Google Books |publisher=Books.google.ca |date= |accessdate=April 10, 2014|isbn=9781896413433 |year=1997 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legacy.com/obituaries/montrealgazette/obituary.aspx?n=mary-harquail-flaherty&pid=117819420 |title=Mary Harquail Flaherty Obituary: View Mary Flaherty's Obituary by The Gazette |publisher=Legacy.com |date= |accessdate=April 10, 2014}}</ref> His parents were from [[New Brunswick]], his father from [[Loggieville, New Brunswick|Loggieville]] and his mother from [[Campbellton, New Brunswick|Campbellton]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fin.gc.ca/n12/12-143_1-eng.asp |title=Archived - Remarks by the Honourable Jim Flaherty, Minister of Finance, to the Fredericton Chamber of Commerce |publisher=Fin.gc.ca |date=November 13, 2012 |accessdate=April 10, 2014}}</ref> He was the sixth of eight children.<ref name=\"Jim Flaherty, 64, dies at Ottawa home one month after resigning as finance minister\"/> He attended Bishop Whelan High School and [[Loyola High School (Montreal)|Loyola High School, Montreal]]. Flaherty attended [[Princeton University]], where he received a [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree in sociology and graduated [[cum laude]] in 1970.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/rob-magazine/one-day-well-look-back-and-thank-jim-flaherty/article575748/?page=all |title=One day, we'll look back and thank Jim Flaherty |date=August 26, 2010 |first=Kevin |last=Carmichael |accessdate=April 11, 2014 |newspaper=The Globe and Mail }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.princeton.edu/canadian/history/CanadianStudiesAnnualReport2007-08.pdf |title=Annual Report for Academic Year 2007\u201308 |accessdate=April 11, 2014 |publisher=Princeton University |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130918201834/http://www.princeton.edu/canadian/history/CanadianStudiesAnnualReport2007-08.pdf |archivedate=September 18, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> He wrote his senior thesis on the sensitivity training at [[Camp X]], a military training institute in Ontario.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://dailyprincetonian.com/news/2014/04/news-and-notes-flaherty-70-former-canadian-finance-minister-dies-at-64/ |title=News and Notes: Flaherty \u201970, former Canadian finance minister, dies at 64 |newspaper=The Daily Princetonian |date=April 10, 2014 |accessdate=April 11, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140819065826/http://dailyprincetonian.com/news/2014/04/news-and-notes-flaherty-70-former-canadian-finance-minister-dies-at-64/ |archive-date=August 19, 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He then received a [[Bachelor of Laws]] degree from [[Osgoode Hall Law School]] of [[York University]].\n\nHe practised law for 20 years<ref>{{cite web|title=The Hon Jim Flaherty, PC, MP, MP--Whitby Oshawa|url=http://www.jimflahertymp.ca/jim-flaherty/about-jim|accessdate=February 24, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140228160726/http://www.jimflahertymp.ca/jim-flaherty/about-jim|archivedate=February 28, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref>  before formally entering politics in 1995. He was a founding partner of Flaherty Dow Elliott after splitting from Gilbert Wright and Flaherty. Flaherty Dow Elliott & McCarthy LLP, as it is now known, is a law firm specializing in motor vehicle accident and personal injury litigation.\n\n==Provincial politics==\nHe first ran for the [[Legislative Assembly of Ontario|Ontario legislature]] in the [[1990 Ontario general election|provincial election of 1990]], finishing third against [[Ontario New Democratic Party|New Democrat]] [[Drummond White]] and [[Ontario Liberal Party|Liberal]] [[Allan Furlong]] in the riding of [[Durham Centre (provincial electoral district)|Durham Centre]]. He ran again and was elected in the [[1995 Ontario general election|1995 election]].<ref name=\"20years=trinh\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/jim-flaherty-s-20-years-in-politics-1.2577577|title=Jim Flaherty's 20 years in politics|last=Theresa Do|first=Trinh|date=Mar 18, 2014|website=cbc.ca|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=Apr 10, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Cabinet===\nHe was named [[Ministry of Labour (Ontario)|Minister of Labour]] in the [[Cabinet (government)|cabinet]] of [[List of Ontario Premiers|Premier]] [[Mike Harris]] on October 10, 1997, and kept this position until after the [[1999 Ontario general election|1999 election]]. He also served as interim [[Solicitor General of Ontario|Solicitor General]] and [[Ministry of Correctional Services|Minister of Correctional Services]] from April 27 to July 27, 1998.<ref name=\"20years=trinh\" />\n\nFlaherty was re-elected in the [[1999 Ontario general election|1999 election]] in the redistributed riding of Whitby\u2013Ajax, and was named [[Attorney General of Ontario|Attorney General]] with responsibility for [[Ministry of Aboriginal Affairs (Ontario)|Native Affairs]] on June 17, 1999. On February 8, 2001, he was appointed [[Ministry of Finance (Ontario)|Minister of Finance]] and [[Deputy Premier of Ontario|Deputy Premier]]. He was a key promoter of tax credits for parents sending their children to private and denominational schools, which the Tories had campaigned against in 1999.<ref name=\"20years=trinh\" /> In June 2001, Flaherty was evicted from his constituency office in a theatrical action by [[Ontario Coalition Against Poverty]] which aimed to bring home the effects of his policies.<ref name=\"Deed\">{{cite journal |last1=Coulter |first1=Kendra |title=Solidarity in Deed: Poor People's Organizations, Unions, and the Politics of Antipoverty Work in Ontario |journal=Anthropology of Work Review |date=December 2012 |volume=33 |issue=2 |pages=101\u2013112 |doi=10.1111/j.1548-1417.2012.01083.x}}</ref>\n\n===2002 Ontario PC leadership bid===\nFlaherty ran to succeed Harris in the [[2002 Progressive Conservative Party of Ontario leadership election|2002 PC leadership election]], but lost to frontrunner [[Ernie Eves]], his predecessor as finance minister. Flaherty's campaign featured attacks on Eves, calling him a \"serial waffler\" and a \"pale, pink imitation of Dalton McGuinty\".<ref>[http://www.sesresearch.com/news/in_the_news/NationalPostJ31.pdf \"Flaherty gets personal with attack on Eves\"], ''[[National Post]]'', January 31, 2002</ref><ref name=\"20years=trinh\" />\n\nFlaherty's leadership campaign focused on \"law and order\" themes, and one of his proposals was to make [[homelessness]] illegal. His purported plan was to have special constables encourage homeless persons to seek out shelters or hospitals. He argued that his policy would save the lives of homeless persons; leadership rival [[Elizabeth Witmer]] and other critics described it as callous, and ineffective against the root causes of homelessness.<ref>{{cite news |title= Activist thought Flaherty joking |author= Heather Capannelli |page= A5 |newspaper= The Globe and Mail|date= February 16, 2002| publisher = via Proquest (subscription required) }}</ref><ref name=\"20years=trinh\" />\n\nFlaherty also promised to implement further [[tax cut]]s, carry through with plans to create a tax credit for parents sending their children to private school, and [[privatization|privatizing]] the [[Liquor Control Board of Ontario]]. Flaherty also emerged as a [[social conservative]] in this campaign, particularly a staunch stance against [[abortion]] and his association with [[anti-abortion]] groups. On April 15, 2002, Eves demoted him to the less-prominent position of Minister of Enterprise, Opportunity and Innovation. Flaherty retained this position until the Tories were defeated in the [[2003 Ontario general election|provincial election of 2003]]. Flaherty himself was re-elected by a reduced margin.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/ontariovotes2003/riding/096/ |title=Ontario Votes 2003: Whitby-Ajax |publisher=CBC.ca |date=2003-10-02 |accessdate=2014-04-11}}</ref><ref name=\"20years=trinh\" />\n\n===Opposition and 2004 Ontario PC leadership bid===\nFollowing the defeat of the Conservatives, Eves announced that he would resign as leader in 2004. Flaherty declared himself a candidate to succeed him, but was defeated by [[John Tory]] by a margin of 54 percent to 46 percent on the second ballot of the [[2004 Progressive Conservative Party of Ontario leadership election|PC leadership election]] held on September 18, 2004. His supporters included former cabinet ministers [[John Baird (Canadian politician)|John Baird]], [[Tim Hudak]] and [[Norm Sterling]].<ref name=\"20years=trinh\" /> His 2004 leadership campaign was similar to that of 2002. He emphasized [[Fiscal conservatism|fiscally conservative]] themes, including further tax cuts and greater privatization. He promised to create EXCEL scholarships, whereby students attaining high grades in high school would have half their university tuition paid by the government. Until 2005, Flaherty served as [[Shadow Cabinet|finance critic]] in [[John Tory]]'s shadow cabinet.<ref name=\"20years=trinh\" /><ref>{{cite news|author=Richard Mackie |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/flaherty-klees-win-key-roles-in-torys-shadow-cabinet/article1004880/ |title=Flaherty, Klees win key roles in Tory's shadow cabinet |newspaper=The Globe and Mail |accessdate=2014-04-11}}</ref>\n\n==Federal Finance Minister==\n[[File:Canadian Finance Minister Jim Flaherty and Irish President Mary McAleese.jpg|thumb|Flaherty stands behind Irish President [[Mary McAleese]]]]\n\nOn June 13, 2005, the Canadian news [[website]] bourque.org reported that a meeting of prominent Conservative organizers and fundraisers had been held to plan for a Flaherty bid for the leadership of the federal party should [[Stephen Harper]] resign.\nIn December 2005, the [[2006 Canadian federal election|2006 general election]] was called. Flaherty resigned his seat in the Ontario legislature to run for the [[Conservative Party of Canada]] in the riding of [[Whitby\u2014Oshawa]], narrowly unseating incumbent [[Judi Longfield]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/canadavotes2006/riding/206/ |title=Canada Votes 2006: Whitby-Oshawa |publisher=CBC.ca |date= |accessdate=2014-04-11}}</ref>\n\nFlaherty's wife, [[Christine Elliott]], won Flaherty's former provincial seat in a [[by-election]], defeating Longfield who was running as the [[Ontario Liberal Party|provincial Liberal]] candidate. This marked the first time in Canadian history that a husband and wife have simultaneously represented the same electoral district at two different levels of government.\n\nOn February 6, 2006, Flaherty was sworn in as [[Minister of Finance (Canada)|Minister of Finance]] in Stephen Harper's new Conservative [[Canadian Cabinet|Cabinet]].<ref>[http://www.canada.com/nationalpost/news/story.html?id=79e62b28-720f-461d-8820-da827d78406f 'Western Tories may miss out on Cabinet posts'] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160106235956/http://www.canada.com/nationalpost/news/story.html?id=79e62b28-720f-461d-8820-da827d78406f |date=January 6, 2016 }}, ''[[National Post]]'', January 16, 2006</ref>\nHe was also appointed Minister Responsible for the Greater Toronto Area. In his capacity as Minister of Finance, he served as a Governor of the World Bank and the International Monetary Fund.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jimflahertymp.ca/jim-flaherty/about-jim |title=About Jim |publisher=Jimflahertymp.ca |accessdate=April 10, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140228160726/http://www.jimflahertymp.ca/jim-flaherty/about-jim |archivedate=February 28, 2014 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nHe announced his resignation from the cabinet on March 18, 2014.<ref>{{cite news |title=Jim Flaherty resigns post as Finance Minister; Joe Oliver to replace him, sources say |url=https://nationalpost.com/news/politics/finance-minister-jim-flaherty-resigns |accessdate=January 30, 2019 |work=[[National Post]] |date=March 18, 2014 |language=en-CA}}</ref>\n\n===October 31, 2006, income trust announcement===\nFlaherty was a central figure in the debate surrounding the [[Income trust#The Conservatives propose new rules for income trusts|new proposed rules for taxation of Canadian income trusts]]. His announcement on October 31, 2006 of a rule change to tax [[income trust]]s levelled the playing field between forms of business such that businesses operating as income trusts no longer enjoyed a tax advantage over businesses operating as corporations.  The announcement was accompanied by a further planned reduction in the corporate rate so that the two moves together were not expected to generate additional revenue for the government.\n\nFlaherty said that income trusts would cost the government $500 million annually in lost tax revenue and shift the burden onto ordinary people.<ref>{{cite news | author = ''[[Global National]]'' | title = Exclusive: Flaherty received death threats | publisher = Global National TV | url = http://www.canada.com/globaltv/national/story.html?id=539d04fe-471d-4cfa-9fc6-af81edc7e085 | date = February 1, 2007 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070325125029/http://www.canada.com/globaltv/national/story.html?id=539d04fe-471d-4cfa-9fc6-af81edc7e085 | archivedate = March 25, 2007 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> The Canadian Association of Income Trust Investors said that foreign takeovers of Canadian income trusts have had the opposite effect and caused decrease in federal government tax revenues.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://caiti-online-media.blogspot.com/2007/09/primewest-energy-trust-bought-for.html |title=Primewest Energy Trust -Bought for Nothing Down & No Income Taxes |publisher=Caiti-online-media.blogspot.com |date=September 27, 2007 |accessdate=April 10, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://network.nationalpost.com/np/blogs/francis/archive/2007/10/01/takeovers-income-trust.aspx |title=Canada Under {{sic{{!}}Se{{!}}ige{{!}}hide=y}}: Thanks Harper and Flaherty |access-date=January 4, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071224034853/http://network.nationalpost.com/np/blogs/francis/archive/2007/10/01/takeovers-income-trust.aspx |archive-date=December 24, 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n[[Diane Francis]], editor-at-large for the ''[[National Post]]'', urged that the rule changes be recanted, arguing that there were flaws in the policy which hurt ordinary, hard-working Canadian investors.<ref>{{cite news | author = Diane Francis | title = Trusts proposal must be recanted | publisher = Financial Post | url = http://www.caiti.info/resources/diane_francis_articles.pdf |format=PDF| date = December 9, 2006 }}</ref>\n\nSpecial hearings by the House of Commons Standing Committee on Finance commenced January 30, 2007. [[John McCallum]], the Liberal finance critic, asked Flaherty to explain the reasoning behind the change in income trust tax policy. McCallum said \"Your first problem is that having lured hundreds of thousands of ordinary Canadians into income trusts by promising not to raise taxes you then cut them off at the knees.\"<ref>{{cite news | author = John MacCallum | title = Your first problem is that having lured hundreds of thousands of ordinary Canadians into income trusts by promising not to raise taxes you then cut them off at the knees | newspaper = National Post | url = http://www.caiti.info/resources/john_mccallum_op_ed.pdf |format=PDF| date = January 3, 2007 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | author = CAITI | title = Mr. Harper Is this what you mean by Transparency? | publisher = CAITI | url = http://www.caiti.info/resources/redacted.pdf |format=PDF| date = February 8, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nOn February 28, 2007, the committee released their report, ''Taxing Income Trusts: Reconcilable or Irreconcilable differences?'', recommending a reduction of the proposed tax to 10 percent from 31.5 percent.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.caiti.info/resources/income_trust_report.pdf |title=Taxing Income Trusts: Reconcilable or Irreconcilable differences? (application/pdf Object) |publisher=www.caiti.info |accessdate=September 16, 2010 }}</ref>\n\n====Fullard opposition====\nOn August 21, 2008, Brent Fullard, president of the Canadian Association of Income Trust Investors, challenged Flaherty to debate supposed tax leakage associated with income trusts. Fullard announced he would put up $50,000, payable to his favourite charity. Given the minister's \"current crusade on financial literacy\", Fullard believed a suitable charitable cause would be a scholarship for business education. \"By doing this we could help repair the damage caused by the Minister's statement that Ontario is the last place to invest.\"<ref>{{cite web|first1=Barry|last1=Critchley|title=Flaherty's $50,000 challenge|accessdate=2014-04-13|year=2008|publisher=[[Financial Post]]|website=financialpost.com|url=http://www.financialpost.com/analysis/columnists/story.html?id=67793cff-2765-40f4-b7c4-da81bc190f09|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140414110955/http://www.financialpost.com/analysis/columnists/story.html?id=67793cff-2765-40f4-b7c4-da81bc190f09|archivedate=April 14, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Flaherty turned down the request. \"The tax fairness plan is law. The Minister made his position clear before the finance committee and there is no need for further debate,\" according to his press spokesperson.<ref>{{cite web\n| first1 = Barry\n| last1 = Critchley\n| title = A tale of two documents\n| accessdate = 2014-04-13\n| date = August 22, 2008\n| publisher = [[Financial Post]]\n| website = financialpost.com\n| url = http://www.financialpost.com/scripts/story.html?id=23b64120-93fc-4783-84f6-3b70d3a7f0fd&k=97729\n| url-status = dead\n| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140414121015/http://www.financialpost.com/scripts/story.html?id=23b64120-93fc-4783-84f6-3b70d3a7f0fd&k=97729\n| archivedate = April 14, 2014\n| df = mdy-all\n}}</ref>\n\n===Registered Disability Savings Plan===\nIn Budget 2007, Flaherty introduced the [[Registered Disability Savings Plan]] (RDSP). The RDSP is a long-term savings plan to help Canadians with disabilities and their families save.<ref>{{cite news |last=Galloway |first=Gloria |date=10 April 2014 |title=10 major moments in Flaherty\u2019s finance tenure |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/10-major-moments-in-flahertys-finance-tenure/article17924986/ |newspaper=The Globe and Mail |location=Toronto ON |publisher= |accessdate=10 April 2014 }}</ref> The RDSP resembles its other saving counterparts, the RRSP and the RESP, and is meant to ensure a secure future for people with disabilities. The Government assists these families by contributing through grants and bonds that supplement contributions.<ref name=\"servicecanada1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.servicecanada.gc.ca/eng/goc/rdsp.shtml |title=Registered Disability Savings Plan |publisher=Service Canada |accessdate=10 April 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Tax-Free Savings Account===\nIn Budget 2008, Flaherty introduced the [[Tax-Free Savings Account]] (TFSA), a flexible, registered, general-purpose savings vehicle that allows Canadians to earn tax-free investment income to more easily meet lifetime savings needs.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tfsa.gc.ca/ |title=Tax-Free Savings Account |publisher=Government of Canada |accessdate=10 April 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140517040846/http://tfsa.gc.ca/ |archivedate=May 17, 2014 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe measure, which came into effect on January 2, 2009, has clear differences with the Registered Retirement Savings Plan (RRSP). There is a tax deduction for contributions to an RRSP, and withdrawals of contributions and investment income are all taxable. In contrast, there are no tax deductions for contributions to a TFSA. Beginning in 2013, contribution room in the TFSA has increased to $5,500 per calendar year. The Canada Revenue Agency describes the difference between the TFSA and an RRSP as follows: \"An RRSP is primarily intended for retirement. The TFSA is like an RRSP for everything else in your life.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Boggs |first=Talbot |date= 22 February 2012 |title=Consider both RRSPs and TFSAs  |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/globe-investor/personal-finance/consider-both-rrsps-and-tfsas/article548181/ |newspaper=The Globe and Mail |location=Toronto ON |publisher= |accessdate= 10 April 2014}}</ref>\n\nFlaherty's measure was supported by many organizations, including the [[C.D. Howe Institute]], which stated: \"This tax policy gem is very good news for Canadians, and Mr. Flaherty and his government deserve credit for a novel program.\"<ref>{{cite news |title= TFSAs: the biggest thing since RRSPs |author= Finn Poschmann |page= FP18 |newspaper= National Post |date= February 27, 2008| publisher = }}</ref>\n\n===EUROMoney Magazine ===\nIn 2009, Flaherty received an award from EUROMoney Magazine, naming him [[Euromoney Finance Minister of the Year|Finance Minister of the Year]]. Flaherty is the first Canadian to hold this honour. It says he \"enhanced his country's reputation for sound fiscal policy that takes full account of social justice, while a strong regulatory regime has kept the financial sector out of the chaos.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.euromoney.com/Article/2297318/Finance-minister-of-the-year-Jim-Flaherty-Canada.html |title=Banking industry news & analysis of international finance &#124; Euromoney magazine |publisher=Euromoney.com |date= |accessdate=April 10, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Federation of Canadian Municipalities report on infrastructure===\n\nFlaherty responded to a report from the [[Federation of Canadian Municipalities]] that suggested that cities had an infrastructure deficit of $123 billion and the federal government should step up with some cash with the suggestion cities should stop \"whining\" and repair their own crumbling infrastructure.\n\n[[Calgary]] Mayor [[Dave Bronconnier]] claimed Flaherty sidestepped responsibility for billions in infrastructure dollars being sought, when Flaherty advised municipalities to \"do their job\" because the feds are \"not in the pothole business\". \"Let\u2019s get on with the job and stop complaining about it and do their job\", Flaherty continued, noting the Building Canada fund will inject $33 billion into cities to help deal with the infrastructure crunch. However Bronconnier said the plan is merely a \"repackaging\" of a number of pre-existing funding arrangements.<ref>{{cite web\n |url          = http://www.dcnonl.com/article/id25251\n |title        = Calgary mayor keeps hard hat and shovel at the ready for Jim Flaherty\n |publisher    = Daily Commercial News and Construction Record\n |accessdate   = February 21, 2008\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20080311102632/http://www.dcnonl.com/article/id25251\n |archive-date = March 11, 2008\n |url-status     = dead\n |df           = mdy-all\n}}</ref> The Building Canada Fund was strongly criticized for being designed to fail, due to excessive red tape, which has delayed much of the funding from being awarded.<ref>\n{{cite web |url=http://www2.canada.com/reginaleaderpost/news/viewpoints/story.html?id=0186111b-896d-469b-b0f6-43346a03fd3c&p=1 |title=Watch the fine print in Tory promises |accessdate=2014-04-13 |last1=Mandryk |website=canada.com |publisher=[[Postmedia News]] |first1=Murray |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140414063135/http://www2.canada.com/reginaleaderpost/news/viewpoints/story.html?id=0186111b-896d-469b-b0f6-43346a03fd3c&p=1 |archivedate=April 14, 2014 |df=mdy-all }} \n</ref>\n\n[[Mississauga]] Mayor [[Hazel McCallion]] went further by issuing a challenge to Flaherty to publicly debate the need for permanent federal funding for the repair and upkeep of municipal roads and bridges. McCallion said \"Flaherty has stated in the media that some of the municipalities have not kept up with infrastructure and did not establish adequate reserves. Well, I can tell him that he is dead wrong. The facts are that Mississauga has carefully set aside reserves for infrastructure for years.\" McCallion noted that cities are trying to maintain 58 per cent of public infrastructure with eight cents of every tax dollar.<ref>\n{{cite web\n|url=http://www.mississauganews.com/article/10479\n|title=Hazel calls out the Finance Minister - The Mississauga News - Mississauga.com\n|publisher=www.mississauganews.com\n|accessdate=February 21, 2008\n|last=Chin\n|first=Joe\n}}\n</ref> Flaherty did not accept Hazel McCallion's offer to debate.<ref>\n{{cite news\n|url=https://www.thestar.com/opinion/columnists/2008/01/25/in_this_corner_a_tory_minister_wearing_blinders.html\n|title=In this corner, a Tory minister wearing blinders\n|publisher=www.thestar.com\n|accessdate=February 21, 2008\n|last=Hume\n|first=Christopher\n| location=Toronto\n| date=January 25, 2008\n}}\n</ref>\n\n===Department of Finance contracts questioned===\nFlaherty said his office broke government contracting rules in hiring MacPhie & Company to help write the 2007 budget speech and provide advice on how to sell the document. MacPhie & Company was awarded the $122,000 contract without tender by Flaherty's office.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://canadianpress.google.com/article/ALeqM5icnUoJmXDHEK4LdEVO1eZYb3ir1g |title=The Canadian Press: Opposition asks for reviews of contract to Flaherty speech writer |publisher=canadianpress.google.com |accessdate=2008-02-01 |last= |first= }}{{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> On February 7, 2008, Liberal finance critic [[John McCallum]] formally called on [[Auditor General of Canada|Auditor General]] [[Sheila Fraser]] to conduct an audit into the untendered contract awarded by Flaherty to MacPhie & Company for work done in advance of the 2007 budget.<ref name=\"brennan1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/News/Canada/article/303484#|title=  Flaherty contracts questioned|work=TheStar|accessdate=February 14, 2008|last=Brennan|first=Richard| location=Toronto| date=February 14, 2008}}</ref>\n\nThe ''[[Toronto Star]]'' determined that several people who supported Flaherty when he was an [[Executive Council of Ontario|Ontario cabinet]] minister or who supported his two failed bids to lead the Ontario Tories were awarded employment contracts or given appointments.<ref name=\"brennan1\"/> The employment contracts awarded were under the $25,000 Treasury Board contract bidding limit. Bronwen Evans received a $24,877.50 contract to write speeches for Flaherty from June 2006 until last February.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.fin.gc.ca/scripts/contracts-contrats/reports-rapports-eng.asp?r=c&refNum=6007612A&q=1&yr=2006\n |title=Disclosure of Contracts Over $10,000\n |work=fin.gc.ca\n |accessdate=October 17, 2010\n}}</ref> David Curtain, who worked on Flaherty's Ontario leadership campaign, received $24,877.50 to write the finance minister's first budget speech. Curtain was also paid $3,350 to write a keynote address earlier in 2008 for Flaherty. Lawyer James Love, who donated $63,000 to Flaherty over two leadership campaigns, was appointed to the Royal Canadian Mint. Another Flaherty donor, Carol Hansell, was appointed to the board of directors of the [[Bank of Canada]] in October 2006. Toronto family law lawyer Sara Beth Mintz, an Ontario Progressive Conservative Party vice-president, received $24,900 for budget \"analysis, assessment and advice\".<ref>{{cite web\n |url= http://www.fin.gc.ca/scripts/contracts-contrats/reports-rapports-eng.asp?r=c&refNum=6008932&q=4&yr=2006\n |title=Disclosure of Contracts Over $10,000\n |work=fin.gc.ca\n |accessdate=October 17, 2010\n}}</ref> MacPhie & Company also got another contract for $24,645 for work done on Advantage Canada, a long-term, national economic plan.<ref>{{cite web\n |url= http://www.fin.gc.ca/scripts/contracts-contrats/reports-rapports-eng.asp?r=c&refNum=6008331&q=3&yr=2006\n |title=Disclosure of Contracts Over $10,000\n |work=fin.gc.ca\n |accessdate=October 17, 2010\n}}</ref> Opposition parties said they were suspicious that contracts were coming in just under $25,000 in order to give business to Flaherty's friends and supporters.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=https://www.thestar.com/News/Canada/article/303484#|title=  Flaherty contracts questioned\n|work=TheStar|accessdate=February 14, 2008|last=Brennan|first=Richard| location=Toronto| date=February 14, 2008}}</ref>\n\nOn May 13, 2008, Flaherty appeared before the Public Accounts committee, facing questions about multiple sole-sourced contracts worth more than $300,000 that were given by the government.<ref>\n{{cite news\n|url=https://nationalpost.com/news/canada/story.html?id=512600\n|archive-url=https://archive.is/20080516005636/http://www.nationalpost.com/news/canada/story.html?id=512600\n|url-status=dead\n|archive-date=May 16, 2008\n|title=Flaherty grilled over untendered communications contracts\n|newspaper=National Post\n|accessdate=May 13, 2008\n|last=Fitzpatrick\n|first=Meagan\n}}\n</ref> Flaherty says he was unaware his former chief of staff broke government rules in handing a well-connected Tory an untendered contract to write the 2007 budget speech.<ref>\n{{cite web\n|url=http://canadianpress.google.com/article/ALeqM5hC85lSgl9cX-zg9HGBYbVu2QIBaQ\n|title=The Canadian Press: Flaherty says unaware $122,000 speech contract to supporter improper\n|publisher=Canadian Press\n|accessdate=May 13, 2008\n|last=\n|first=\n}}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url          = http://www.disclosed.ca/?keyword=MacPhie\n |title        = Disclosed: Search results for MacPhie\n |work         = disclosed.ca\n |accessdate   = October 17, 2010\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110706175245/http://www.disclosed.ca/?keyword=MacPhie\n |archive-date = July 6, 2011\n |url-status     = dead\n |df           = mdy-all\n}}</ref>\n\n===Foreign Account Tax Compliance Act===\nThe Foreign Account Tax Compliance Act is American legislation that requires cooperation, legal and financial, from Canada (and other nations), in order to be implemented. The official reason given for this legislation was efforts to crack down on tax evasion. However, in a letter Flaherty sent to U.S. newspapers in September 2011, he said the law would waste resources  and raise privacy concerns.  On February 5, 2014, Flaherty signed Canada on as a participant to FATCA through an [[FATCA agreement between Canada and the United States|Intergovernmental Agreement]] (IGA).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/fatca-facts-what-canadians-need-to-know-about-new-u-s-tax-law-1.2493882 |title=FATCA facts: What Canadians need to know about new U.S. tax law - Canada - CBC News |publisher=Cbc.ca |date= |accessdate=April 10, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Abolishing the penny===\nWhile announcing Economic Action Plan 2012 on March 29 in the House of Commons, Flaherty explained that, by February 2013, the government would be phasing out the penny. The cost to produce each new penny was 1.6 cents, which exceeded the penny's face value by 0.6 cents. The estimated savings for taxpayers from phasing out the penny is about $11 million a year. Even though the government eliminated the penny from circulation, Canadians can continue to use pennies for cash transactions indefinitely for businesses that choose to accept them or they can redeem rolled pennies at their financial institutions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fin.gc.ca/1cent/toolkit-boite-a-outils-eng.asp |title=Toolkit for Businesses: Phasing out the Penny |publisher=Fin.gc.ca |date= |accessdate=April 10, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.nationalpost.com/2012/03/30/canada-penny-federal-budget-one-cent-coin/ |title=Canadian penny drops in federal budget as Jim Flaherty signals end of one cent coin &#124; National Post |publisher=News.nationalpost.com |date= |accessdate=April 10, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Building Canada Plan===\nOn May 21, 2013, Flaherty introduced his 2013 Budget. The Budget contained a new Building Canada Plan for the construction of public infrastructure such as roads, bridges, transit and port facilities.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.journalofcommerce.com/article/id54666/profenvironmental |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130426233847/http://www.journalofcommerce.com/article/id54666/profenvironmental |url-status=dead |archive-date=April 26, 2013 |title=Building Canada Plan maps infrastructure spending \u2013 Journal of Commerce |publisher=Journalofcommerce.com |accessdate=April 10, 2014 }}</ref> The plan provides $53 billion in investments to support local and economic infrastructure projects, including more than $47 billion in new funding over 10 years, starting in 2014\u20132015.<ref>{{cite web |author=Diane Crocker Published on |url=http://www.thewesternstar.com/News/Local/2013-03-22/article-3205324/Greeley-pleased-to-see-new-Building-Canada-plan-in-federal-budget/1 |title=Greeley pleased to see new Building Canada plan in federal budget - Local |publisher=The Western Star |accessdate=April 10, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130802192839/http://www.thewesternstar.com/News/Local/2013-03-22/article-3205324/Greeley-pleased-to-see-new-Building-Canada-plan-in-federal-budget/1 |archivedate=August 2, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Budgets presented===\nFlaherty presented nine budgets to the Canadian Parliament as Minister of Finance.\n* [[2006 Canadian federal budget]]\n* [[2007 Canadian federal budget]]\n* [[2008 Canadian federal budget]]\n* [[2009 Canadian federal budget]]\n* [[2010 Canadian federal budget]]\n* [[2011 Canadian federal budget]] (presented in March 2011 and again in June).\n* [[2012 Canadian federal budget]]\n* [[2013 Canadian federal budget]]\n* [[2014 Canadian federal budget]]\n\n===Resignation from Cabinet===\nOn March 18, 2014, Flaherty announced that he was resigning as Minister of Finance in order to return to the private sector. While he had openly discussed health challenges associated with managing [[bullous pemphigoid]], including taking prescription steroids, he said the decision was reached after many months of consultation with his family and that his health was not a factor in his decision.<ref>{{cite news|author=Steven Chase |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/i-dont-like-talking-about-this-flaherty-on-battle-with-skin-disease/article8025398/#dashboard/follows/ |title='I don't like talking about this:' Flaherty on battle with skin disease |newspaper=The Globe and Mail |date=January 31, 2013 |accessdate=April 10, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Canada |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/read-jim-flahertys-statement-on-resigning-as-finance-minister/article17551462/#dashboard/follows/ |title=Read Jim Flaherty's statement on resigning as finance minister |newspaper=The Globe and Mail |date=March 18, 2014 |accessdate=April 10, 2014}}</ref> Flaherty continued sitting in the House of Commons as an MP until his death three weeks later.<ref name=\"Jim Flaherty, 64, dies at Ottawa home one month after resigning as finance minister\"/><ref>{{cite news|title=Joe Oliver takes over federal finance portfoliot|url=http://www.ctvnews.ca/politics/joe-oliver-takes-over-federal-finance-portfolio-1.1735916|accessdate=March 19, 2014|newspaper=CTV News|date=March 19, 2014}}</ref>\nAt the time of his resignation, he had been the honour of being the ''Longest continuous serving cabinet minister in a single portfolio'' in the 28th Canadian Ministry.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.parl.gc.ca/Parlinfo/Files/Parliamentarian.aspx?Item=95e9d5a2-e9a6-4037-b6a7-218bfdc01a33&Language=E| accessdate=April 12, 2014|title=PARLINFO - Parliamentarian File - Federal Experience - FLAHERTY, The Hon. James Michael (Jim), P.C., B.A., LL.B.|website=parl.gc.ca}}</ref>\n\n===Honours===\nAn office building in [[Ottawa]], housing employees from the [[Department of Finance (Canada)|Department of Finance]], is named after Flaherty.<ref>https://ottawacitizen.com/news/politics/new-finance-canada-building-named-after-jim-flaherty</ref>\n\nWith the [[2017 Canada Day Honours]], Flaherty was awarded with a posthumous [[Meritorious Service Cross]].<ref name=\"canadagazette.gc.ca\">http://canadagazette.gc.ca/rp-pr/p1/2017/2017-07-01/html/gh-rg-eng.html</ref>\n<center>\n[[File:MSC ribbon-civil.png|100px]][[File:QEII Golden Jubilee Medal ribbon.png|100px]][[File:QEII Diamond Jubilee Medal ribbon.png|100px]]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:silver;\" align=\"center\"\n|Ribbon || Description || Notes\n|-\n|[[File:MSC ribbon-civil.png|100px]] || [[Meritorious Service Cross]]||\n* 2017: Christine Elliott and the late Jim Flaherty founded Abilities Centre, a unique, world-class facility in Whitby that engages people of all ages and abilities in sports, the arts and personal growth activities. Thanks to their dedicated support, the centre has become a local and international example of inclusiveness where everyone can participate equally.<ref>https://www.gg.ca/en/honours/recipients/136-52994</ref><ref name=\"canadagazette.gc.ca\">http://canadagazette.gc.ca/rp-pr/p1/2017/2017-07-01/html/gh-rg-eng.html</ref>\n|-\n|[[File:QEII Golden Jubilee Medal ribbon.png|100px]] || [[Queen Elizabeth II Golden Jubilee Medal]] for Canada||\n* 2002:<ref>https://www.gg.ca/en/honours/recipients/125-32011</ref>\n|-\n|[[File:QEII Diamond Jubilee Medal ribbon.png|100px]] || [[Queen Elizabeth II Diamond Jubilee Medal]] for Canada||\n* 2012: As the [[Minister of the Crown]] and as an elected Member of the [[House of Commons of Canada]], The Honourable James M. Flaherty was awarded the medal as a member of the [[Canadian order of precedence]].<ref>https://www.gg.ca/en/honours/recipients/126-685</ref>\n|-\n\n|}\n</center>\n\n==Personal life and death==\n[[File:Flaherty state funeral DSC 0105 (13905494015).jpg|thumb|right|Media overlooking a crowd fronting the [[Cathedral Church of St. James (Toronto)|Cathedral Church of St. James]] in Toronto during Flaherty's state funeral on 16 April 2014]]\n\nFlaherty grew up in a [[Roman Catholic|Catholic]] family in [[Montreal]], and was of part [[Irish people|Irish]] descent. As a youth he was an avid [[Ice hockey|hockey]] player and won a hockey scholarship to [[Princeton University]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Perkins|first=Tara|title=Jim Flaherty: Time off the hustings, tucking into soup|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/careers/careers-leadership/jim-flaherty-time-off-the-hustings-tucking-into-soup/article576562/?page=all|newspaper=The Globe and Mail|date=April 8, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"vallance2002\">{{cite news|last=Vallance-Jones|first=Fred|title=1960s frustrating era for young Jim Flaherty|newspaper=The Spectator (Hamilton, Ontario)|page = A01|date=March 20, 2002}}</ref>\n\nThose familiar with Flaherty's work as a lawyer noted his dogged determination and a strong work ethic. One colleague,  Hamilton lawyer John Soule said, \"He is a driven person&nbsp;... and certainly is prepared to do what is necessary in terms of time and hard work to achieve what he believes is right\".<ref name=\"vallance2002\"/>  He assisted in several volunteer causes, including being the president of the Head Injury Association of Durham Region in Ontario.<ref name=\"vallance2002\"/>\n\nHis widow, Christine Elliott, was the [[Progressive Conservative Party of Ontario|Progressive Conservative]] Member of Provincial Parliament for Oshawa&ndash;Whitby, east of Toronto and Deputy Leader of the Opposition until her resignation in August 2015. The couple lived in Whitby and have triplet sons John, Gaelen and Quinn, who were born in 1991.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.thestar.com/moneyville/article/870692 | title = Daw: 4 tips Jim Flaherty is giving his three sons| publisher = Toronto Star (Moneyville) | date = October 4, 2010}}</ref> Her son Galen, used to work for Doug Ford, then [[Etobicoke]] councillor.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/toronto/a-young-flaherty-joins-doug-fords-staff/article598347/|title=A young Flaherty joins Doug Ford's staff|access-date=2018-02-28}}</ref>    Elliott and Flaherty have both championed issues surrounding children with disabilities; their son, John, has a disability.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2014/04/10/jim_flaherty_and_christine_elliott_were_partners_in_life_law_and_politics.html|title=Jim Flaherty and Christine Elliott were partners in life, law, and politics|newspaper=The Toronto Star|author=Robert Benzie|date=2014-10-04}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2013, Flaherty announced he had [[bullous pemphigoid]].<ref name=passes>[http://globalnews.ca/news/1263247/jim-flaherty-passes-away-at-63-reports/ Jim Flaherty passes away at 64], by Erika Tucker, at Global News; published April 10, 2014; retrieved April 10, 2014</ref> He was treated with [[prednisone]].<ref name = \"Boesveld2014\">{{cite news|author = Sarah Boesveld|title = Treatments that suppressed Jim Flaherty\u2019s rare skin disorder had a tremendous effect on him|url = http://news.nationalpost.com/2014/04/10/treatments-that-suppressed-jim-flahertys-rare-skin-disorder-had-a-tremendous-effect-on-him/|newspaper = [[National Post]]|date = April 10, 2014}}</ref> Flaherty died on April 10, 2014, at his home in Ottawa after suffering a heart attack at the age of 64.<ref name=dead>{{cite news|title=Former finance minister Jim Flaherty is dead at 64|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/flaherty/article17919447/|accessdate=April 10, 2014|newspaper=The Globe and Mail|date=April 10, 2014}}</ref>\n\nA [[State funerals in Canada|state funeral]] was held for Flaherty on April 16, 2014, at [[Cathedral Church of St. James (Toronto)|St. James Cathedral]] in Toronto.<ref>{{cite web|author = Laura Peyton|title = Jim Flaherty to have state funeral Wednesday|url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/jim-flaherty-to-have-state-funeral-wednesday-1.2607292|publisher = [[CBC News]]|date = April 11, 2014}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=40em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110810120708/http://www.jimflahertymp.ca/ Jim Flaherty MP] official site\n*{{Canadian Parliament links| parliament = 170343 | parlinfo = 2225 | openparl = jim-flaherty }}\n*{{Ontario MPP biography|ID=35}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{Canadian cabinet member navigational box header |ministry=Mike_Harris}}\n{{ministry box cabinet posts\n| post4preceded = [[Elizabeth Witmer]]\n| post4         = [[Ministry of Labour (Ontario)|Minister of Labour]]\n| post4years    = 1997\u20131999\n| post4note     =\n| post4followed = [[Chris Stockwell]]\n| post3preceded = [[Charles Harnick]]\n| post3         = [[List of Ontario Attorneys General|Attorney General]]\n| post3years    = 1999\u20132001\n| post3note     =\n| post3followed = [[David Young (Ontario politician)|David Young]]\n| post2preceded = [[Ernie Eves]]\n| post2         = [[Deputy Premier of Ontario]]\n| post2years    = 2001\u20132002\n| post2note     =\n| post2followed = [[Elizabeth Witmer]]\n| post1preceded = [[Ernie Eves]]\n| post1         = [[Ministry of Finance (Ontario)|Minister of Finance]]\n| post1years    = 2001\u20132002\n| post1note     =\n| post1followed = [[Janet Ecker]]\n}}\n{{ministry box special cabinet\n| post1preceded = [[Charles Harnick]]\n| post1         = [[Ministry of Aboriginal Affairs (Ontario)|Minister of Aboriginal Affairs]]\n| post1years    = 1999\u20132001\n| post1note     =\n| post1followed = [[David Young (Ontario politician)|David Young]]\n}}\n{{Canadian cabinet member navigational box header |ministry=Ernie_Eves}}\n{{ministry box cabinet posts\n| post1preceded = Position established\n| post1         = [[Minister of Enterprise, Opportunity and Innovation]]\n| post1years    = 2002\u20132003\n| post1note     =\n| post1followed = Position abolished\n}}\n{{Canadian federal ministry navigational box header |ministry=28}}\n{{ministry box cabinet posts\n| post1         = [[Minister of Finance (Canada)|Minister of Finance]]\n| post1years    = 2006\u20132014\n| post1note     =\n| post1preceded = [[Ralph Goodale]]\n| post1followed = [[Joe Oliver (politician)|Joe Oliver]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Harper Ministry}}\n{{Harris Ministry}}\n{{CanMin